<TITLE>Electronic Communication Procedure Guide for Artemis Technical Committees 
</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="John E. Peel">
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1>Web Pages Procedure Guide for Artemis Technical Committees
</H1>

<P>
This procedure guide explains how to create, review, modify, and
publish web pages. The procedures listed here apply to <I>all</I>
parts of the Artemis Project. This includes the Artemis Data Book,
all committees (technical and non-technical), all other committee
procedure guides, and any other information published on the Artemis
Project web site. It also includes a basic style guide for you
to follow when creating web pages for the Artemis Project. The
style guide is meant mainly to provide general guidelines for
publishing web pages. You don't need to use every single style
specified. The idea is to provide a consistent look and feel for
Artemis Project web pages.
<P>
Members of the Artemis <A href="/adb/09/01/ectc.html">Electronic Communications Technical Committee</A>
(ECTC) will handle the job of setting up the communications services
for individual committees and discussion groups, but once those
services are in place each committee or discussion group will
be responsible for managing and maintaining their use of the services.
This includes web pages.
<P>
Since the Artemis communications environment is still &quot;under
construction&quot;, this procedure guide will be updated from
time to time. So it's a good idea to check it regularly.
<H2>Web Pages - An Introduction</H2>

<P>
The Artemis Web Site is the primary source of information about
the Artemis Project and the Artemis Society. Each technical committee
or discussion group should have web pages on the Artemis web site
that describes that committee or discussion group, provides information
about joining the committee or discussion group, and shares completed
and in-progress work being done. To make it easy for people to
join a committee or volunteer for specific tasks, you can set
up web forms to automatically send e-mail to someone on the committee.
Committees can also include current membership information and
current project information on the web pages as well. For an example
of some committee web pages, look at the <A href="/adb/09/01/ectc.html">ECTC web pages</A>.
<H2>The Web Page Publishing Process</H2>

<P>
Publishing web pages includes the following steps:
<UL>
<LI>setting up/Writing the web page
<LI>submitting the web page for a technical and editorial review
<LI>formatting the web page, if this isn't already done
<LI>submitting the web page for <B>final </B>review by the ASI
Board of Directors
<LI>publishing the web page in the Artemis Data Book
</UL>

<H3>Setting Up Web Pages</H3>

<P>
Setting up a web page involves designing, writing, inserting links,
and submitting the web page, or web pages, to the web team for
review. When creating a web page, use the style guide listed later
in this procedure guide. You can either send ASCII text documents
about your web page to the ASI Web Team at <A href="mailto:asi-web@asi.org">asi-web@asi.org</A>,
or you can create the actual web page yourself using an HTML editor,
them submit it to the ASI web team. If you create your own web
page, make sure it conforms to the ASI style guide as much as
possible.
<P>
If you send ASCII text documents, include the following information
about your web page:
<UL>
<LI>links to your new web pages - People browsing the web site
will only find your web pages by following links from other pages.
You should specify one or more existing web pages containing links
to your new pages.
<LI>links to the appropriate technical committee directory, which
can include:
<LI>a description and Purpose of the Committee or Discussion group.
<LI>the current membership list (if you want that information
published).
<LI>graphics, in either .GIF or .JPG format. If you plan on using
any Artemis-approved graphics, such as the &quot;Artemis&quot;
moon on the Artemis Project home page, you should get those graphics
from the Artemis graphics directory. Contact the ASI Web Team
for more details.
<LI>project information, such as which tasks are completed and
which are in progress
<LI>task lists, so viewers can see what tasks need to be done
<LI>information for web forms to join the committee and/or volunteer
for tasks:
<UL>
<LI>specify the e-mail address to send form submissions
<LI>if using a volunteer form, specify a list of tasks to use
for a choice list
</UL>

</UL>

<H3>Submitting the Web Page for Review</H3>

<P>
Once you complete your web page, submit the web page to the head
of your task committee, who reviews it along with someone from
the ASI Web Team. The person(s) reviewing your web page varies,
depending on which committee you're on and the content of your
web page. The review time can also vary for the same reasons.
If there is no task committee, or if the task committee chairperson
is not yet selected, just submit your web page to to the ASI Web
Team at <A href="mailto:asi-web@asi.org">asi-web@asi.org</A>.
<P>
After you make the technical corrections to your web page, the
ASI Editorial Staff does an editorial review. In this review,
our copyeditors &quot;markup&quot; your web page, send back style/formatting
changes to you, then review your corrections. The copyeditors
make sure that your web page meets the general web page styles
outlined in this procedure guide. This verifies that the web page's
original intent and logical flow has been preserved through the
editing process.
<H3>Formatting the Web Page</H3>

<P>
This step involves creating the HTML version of your web page.
Once your web page is reviewed and corrected, the ASI Web Team
converts the web page content to HTML format for final review
by the ASI Board of Directors. This may take some time, depending
on your web page's content and work schedules of the ASI Web Team
members building your web page.
<P>
If you've already created the HTML version of your page, it goes
to the ASI Board of Directors for final approval.
<H3>Submitting the Web Page for FINAL Review</H3>

<P>
The ASI Board of Directors has the FINAL say on all web pages
published at the ASI Web Site. At ths point, a Board of Directors
member reviews your web page with its final corrections. Or the
Board of Directors delegates someone on the appropriate committee
to do the final review and make his/her recommendations to the
Board. Once the board makes its decision, the ASI Web Team contacts
you to let you know whether or not the Board approved your web
page.
<H3>Publishing the Web Page</H3>

<P>
The ASI Web Team publishes your just-approved web page to the
ASI Web Site in the appropriate directory. For example, if you're
on the ECTC and your page deals with ECTC issues, your web page
is published in the ECTC directory.
<H2>Web Page Publishing Style Guide</H2>

<P>
This section lists the styles you should use in creating a web
page for the ASI Web Site. Keep in mind that this style guide
is meant to provide general guidelines. You need not use every
single style listed here since every web page's content may vary.
Using this style guide:
<UL>
<LI>makes the ASI Web Team's job easier (and yours!) for reviewing
and updating your web page.
<LI>gives the ASI web pages a consistent look and feel.
</UL>

<P>
This style guide will change as different situations arise, so
be sure to check this page regularly for style guide updates.
If you have any questions or concerns, drop a line to the ASI
Web Team at <A href="mailto:asi-web@asi.org">asi-web@asi.org</A>.
<P>
When developing your web page with the styles listed here, keep
these tips in mind:
<UL>
<LI>Follow a normal essay or technical paper format.
<LI>Use an Artemis Data Book (ADB) page as a format guideline.
<LI>Use active voice in your writing with simple words. If a 5-cent
word does the job, don't use a 10-dollar word! You don't want
to come across as talking down to web page visitors.  Nor do you
want web page readers to scratch their heads wondering what you're
saying.
</UL>

<H3>Title</H3>

<P>
Use the Heading1 style found in Word's Internet Assistant. This
text is 18pt, bold, Times New Roman font.
<H3>Header Styles</H3>

<P>
Use Heading2, Heading3, and Heading4 styles for subheadings in
documents. The style descriptions are:
<UL>
<LI>Heading2 - 16 pt, Times New Roman, no bold or italic, left
justified.
<LI>Heading3 - 14 pt, Times New Roman, no bold or italic, left
justified.
<LI>Heading4 - 12 pt, Times New Roman, no bold or italic, left
justified.
</UL>

<H3>Body Text Styles</H3>

<P>
Keep paragraph text in Times New Roman font, 10pt, left-justified.
Use ACTIVE voice in writing your text, and include as many links
within your text as you can. Don't just list a special section
for web page links; make it easier for readers to link to information
by putting links in your document. If you want to emphasize something
in text, avoid using all caps. Using Bold or Italic (or both)
is just as effective.
<P>
Also, remember to keep the page background white to keep it consistent
with the rest of the Artemis Project pages.
<P>
For link text, make the colors BLUE for links, PURPLE/MAGENTA
for visited links, and RED for active links.
<P>
If listing members of the Artemis Project, include:
<UL>
<LI>the person's name.
<LI>the committee he/she serves on OR his/her title. If you're
listing the committee, include a link to that committee's web
page, or to that committee's task list.
<LI>the e-mail address in parentheses. This should be linked.
<LI>the web page address (if available). This should also be linked.
</UL>

<P>
For example,
<P>
Gregory Bennett - Director, Office of Space Flight (grb@asi.org)
<P>
John Peel - member, ECTC Technical Committee (jpeel@netcom.com)
<H3>Graphics</H3>

<P>
Use .GIF or ..JPG format files. They can either be linked or unlinked.
<H3>Lists (Numbered and Bulleted)</H3>

<P>
Use numbered lists if you're describing a particular procedure,
such as how to contact the Artemis Society, how to join a particular
task committee. You can also use numbered lists to indicate order
of importance. For example, if you're describing the five most
important features of a spacecraft system and wish to list them
in order of importance (1=most important, 5=least important),
a numbered list is the way to go.
<P>
Use bulleted lists if the order of items in a list does not matter.
Also, when using bulleted lists, don't use initial caps. Items
listed in bulleted lists tend to be phrases instead of complete
sentences, so using initial caps would be gramatically incorrect.
<H3>Footers</H3>

<P>
The page footer should contain links to other Artemis pages, as
shown at the bottom of this page. The footer should also contain:
<UL>
<LI>copyright symbol and date, such as Copyright &#169; 1996 Artemis
Society International. You should also include the trademark statement:
</UL>

<P>
<A href="http://www.asi.org/index.html">The Artemis Project</A>,
is a trademark of <A HREF="http://www.tlrc.com/Lrc.html">The Lunar Resources Company</A>.
<UL>
<LI>the web page author - this is you.
<LI>update date -- the date the page was last updated
</UL>

<H3>Information File Contents</H3>

<P>
You should create an information file (.info) for your own records.
You can also send the ASI Web Team a copy of this file for their
benefit, but it's mostly for your records. The file can be an
ASCII text file and should list the following information:
<UL>
<LI>author -- the author of the web page
<LI>description -- a 50-word description of the web page.
<LI>maintainer -- who maintains the web page
<LI>update date -- lists dates and descriptions of revisions
<LI>responsible technical committee -- the technical committee
or technical committee representative that will review your page
<LI>copyright info -- if any is listed. Include the standard ASI
Copyright, which appears at the bottom of this page. It's also
a good idea to include a copyrght statement with the name of the
web page author.
</UL>

<P>
***** CURRENTLY THIS SECTION IS UNDER CONSTRUCTION. MORE DETAILS
WILL FOLLOW SOON! THANKS FOR YOUR PATIENCE. *****
<H2>World Wide Web Conversation Pages</H2>

<P>
The Artemis World Wide Web Conversation Pages are not yet implemented.
Once they are, the conversation pages will be a set of web pages
that provide full access to the discussions going on in the various
mailing lists of the Artemis Project. You will be able to read
previous mailing list messages from these web pages and you will
be able to submit new messages to the mailing lists from the convenience
of a web form. We're also currently evaluating IRC on the web
for realtime online conversations/meetings. We'll keep you posted
of the latest changes.
<P>
To find out what's going on and how you can help implement this
capability, check out the <A href="/adb/09/01/ectc_tasks.html#webserver">Web Server section</A>
of the <A href="/adb/09/01/ectc_tasks.html">ECTC Task List</A>.
<HR>

<P>
