<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Paul Morris' Bio</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><!-- V 1.0 Paul Morris' Bio --><!-- /Bios/morris.paul.html --><IMG SRC="/Gifs/artlogona.gif" align="top"><font size=-2>TM</font><BR><H1>Paul J. Morris</H1><B>Paleontologist, Educator, Computer Consultant</B><HR><H3>Role in the Artemis Project</H3><P><a href="mailto:mole@bio.umass.edu">Paul J. Morris</a> is the chairmanof the <AHREF="/adb/06/07/osf-pg-1.html#0607020103">Lunar Science TechnicalCommittee</a>, where his knowledge of geology and other scientificdisciplines are put to the enormous benefit of the <ahref="/artemis.html">Artemis Project</a>. Paul is also a member of theLunar Mining, Lunar Agriculture Tech Committees. He also lends his talentand insight to the Artemis Project <ahref="/adb/09/03/mailing-lists.html">discussion groups</a>.</P><P>As a member of the Site Selection Tech Committee, Paul is working onprocuring and poring over <a href="/images/asi199600041.gif">images</a> ofthe <a href="/adb/04/01/01/03/">Mare Anguus region</a> for the <ahref="/adb/04/">manned landings</a> and earlier <ahref="/adb/05/05/">telerobot missions</a>. He is also working on a largephoto-composite of the "Angus Bay" region.</P><H3>Education</H3><UL><LH>BA 1984 Colgate University</LH><UL><LI>Geology Major<LI>High Honors in Geology</UL></UL><UL><LH>Ph.D. 1991 Harvard University, Department of Earth and PlanetaryScience</LH><UL><LI>Thesis Area: Invertebrate Paleontology<LI>Thesis Title:<EM> Functional Morphology and Phylogeny: An assessment ofmonophyly in the Kingdom Animalia and in Paleozoic Nearly-planispiralSnail-like Molluscs</EM><LI>Advisors: Stephen J. Gould, Raymond Siever,  Ruth D. Turner</UL></UL><H3>Professional Experience:</H3><H4>Employment</H4><P>1995- Darwin Postdoctoral Fellow, University of Massachusetts, Amherst<BR>1993-1995 Postdoctoral Fellow and Collections Assistant, PaleontologicalResearch Institution, Ithaca, NY<BR>1992-1993 Smithsonian Postdoctoral Fellow, Smithsonian Tropical ResearchInstitution, Panama<BR>1991-1992 Postdoctoral Fellow, Department of Earth and Planetary Sciences,Harvard University</p><H4>Computer Consulting Experience</H4><P>1996 Datamodeler (subcontract) for NSF funded workshop on InvertebratePaleontological Collections Database management<BR>1995-1996 Web Page designer, Paleontological Research Institution<BR>1994 Database Consultant, Panama Paleontology Project<BR>1986 Database Consultant, Invertebrate Paleontology Dept. Museum ofComparative Zoology</p><H4>Professional Societies</H4><P>American Geophysical Union, American Malacological Union, History ofScience Society, International Paleontological Association, PaleontologicalSociety, Paleontological Research Institution, SEPM-Society for SedimentaryGeology.</P><H4>Human Services</H4><P>1987-1991, Staff member of InCommon,  peer counseling hotline at HarvardUniversity.<BR>1987-88, Co-Director of InCommon. <BR>1986-88, EMT part time, Professional Ambulance, Cambridge MA.<BR>1984 (Summer), EMT, full time, Mohawk Ambulance, Schenectady NY.<BR>1982-88, 1995-present  American Red Cross CPR/First Aid Instructor.</P><!-- Nav bar --><hr size = 5><table align=center border=4 cellpadding = 3cellspacing=2><tr><td align=center><b><ahref="http://www.asi.org/"</a>Artemis Project</b><td align=center><b><ahref="http://www.asi.org/asi_index.html"</a>ArtemisSociety</b><td align=center><b><a href="http://www.asi.org/adb/"</a>ArtemisData Book</b><td align=center><b><ahref="http://www.tlrc.com/Artemis_FAQ_toc.html"</a> FAQ</b><tdalign=center><b><ahref="http://www.tlrc.com/Reference_mission.html"</a>ReferenceMission</b><td align=center><b><ahref="http://www.tlrc.com/catalog.html"</a>Catalog</b></tr></table><hr size= 5><font size=-2>Copyright &#169; 1996 Artemis Society Interational.Updated Fri, May 10, 1996<br> "<A HREF="/Artemis.html">The ArtemisProject</A>" is a trademark of <A HREF="http://www.tlrc.com">The LunarResources Company</A>. </font></BODY></HTML>
