<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>1. Basic Overview of the Artemis Project</TITLE></HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<!-- Artemis Data Book -->
<!-- ADB section 1. Project Overview -->
<!-- file: /adb/01/basic-overview.html -->
<!-- Keywords: moonrock regolith sales financing funding marketing
merchandising merchandise comapny experience products distribution tasks
how you can help -->
<!-- v 1.0 -->
<h2 align="center">Artemis Data Book</H2>
<h2 align="center">1. Project Overview</H2>
<h2 align="center">Basic Overview of the Artemis Project</H2>
<I><P ALIGN=CENTER>Greg Bennett</P></I>
<P><HR><P>

<P><a href="/asi_index.html">Artemis Society International</a>, a
non-profit foundation managing a project to
establish a permanent,
self-supporting lunar base as a private venture, needs
your help.  To learn what this is about, explore the WWW site at:</p>

<P align=center><a href="http://www.asi.org/">http://www.asi.org</a><BR>
and speak to our Comm and Info Center,<BR><a
href="mailto:artemis@asi.org">&lt;artemis@asi.org&gt;</a></P>


<H3>Very brief overview of the Artemis Project:</H3>

<P>The initial stages of the <a href="/artemis.html">Artemis Project</a>,
up through establishing the
permanent lunar
base, are funded by <a href="/adb/03/04/">revenues</a> derived <a
href="/adb/03/04/revenue-breakdown.html">mostly</a> from the entertainment value of
space flight.  The spacecraft are built using commercial aircraft standards and
procedures to reduce the cost.  This provides a modest <a
href="/adb/04/02/03/">habitat</a> on the moon and
leaves the <a href="/adb/04/02/01/ltv-notes.html">transportation system</a>
in orbit.</P>

<P>At that point, the project is in the black.
We've learned that it's not a question of <a href="/adb/j/too-risky-for-investors.html">whether this approach will work</a>, but how long it will take.  The more effective we are in building a <a href="/asi_index.html">participating team</a>, the faster we get
there.  If everything goes right (it won't), we could land the first permanent <a href="/adb/04/02/03/">habitat</a> within eight years.</P>

<P>Anticipated growth paths from the <a href="/adb/04/">initial lunar
base</a> include supporting
scientific investigations and exploration, <a
href="/adb/04/03/10/04/oxygen-extraction.html">lunar industries</a> (and their support to other space industries), and  tourism.  The largest <a href="/adb/03/04/long-term-funding.html">revenue producer</a>
among these probably will be <a href="/adb/02/07/02/01/lunacity-hotel.html">tourism</a>.</P>


<H3>What's going on:</H3>

<P><a href="/asi_index.html">Artemis Society International</a> is a <a
href="/asi_member.html">membership</a> organization with <a
href="/adb/07/local-chapters.html">local chapters
and representatives</a> in  
Australia, Canada, France, Great Britain, Ireland, New Zealand, Sweden,  
and the United States.</P>

<P>At the leading edge of this effort is the Society's <a
href="/adb/09/01/ectc.html">Electronic Communication
Technical Committee</a>.  They are just now developing <a
href="/adb/09/overview.html">communication tools</a> toenable a team spread out around the world to work together productively.</P>

<P>On the <a href="/index.html">WWW site</a> you'll find the outline for
the <a href="/adb/">Artemis Data Book</a>, which
organizes all the plans and information related to all aspects of the program.
The Artemis Society's <a href="/adb/06/07/">technical committees</a> and <a
href="/adb/06/08/">project teams</a> are working on the
sundry parts of the program.</P>


<H3>How you can help:</H3>

<P>You'll find a rather long list of "<a
href="/Things_You_Can_Do.html">things you can do</a>" online.  A very
broad range of skills, talents, and resources are needed to make the project
happen; it's a lot more than building and flying
spaceships.  I suspect most interested parties would be interested in
helping fill in the technical blanks in
the <a href="/adb/">Artemis Data Book</a>.  You might also want to help with the organizational work, or participate in the <a href="/adb/03/04/">revenue-producing</a>
side of the project.</P><H3>Why you want to help:</H3>

<P>If the project is successful, it will establish an economic environment where
commercial interests are able to conduct business profitably on the moon and
elsewhere in cislunar space.  That provides a stable <a
href="/adb/03/03/building-financial-base.html">economic foundation</a> for
the resources needed to do whatever you want to do on the moon at the least
possible cost.  Steady continuous development in space is assured, independent
of changing <a href="/adb/03/05/">political</a> environments.</P>

<P>Since the success of the program depends on an <a
href="/adb/07/local-chapters.html">international team</a> to get things
started in many different arenas, several <a
href="/adb/03/royalties-for-volunteers.html">inducements</a> are designed into the program to reward early participation.  For example, all else being equal, priority for use of the available resources will be assigned to indviduals in numerical order by <a href="/asi_index.html">Artemis Society</a> membership
number.  In other words, it won't work to wait and show up eight years from now to help us take the cookies out of the oven.</P>


<H3>What the Artemis Project is not:</H3>

<P>The Artemis Project is not a government program.  Like any corporate entity, governments may be <a href="/adb/10/">program participants</a>, suppliers, or customers;
however, some restrictions on government participation are necessary to maintain the basic character of the project.</P>

<P>The Artemis Project should not be confused with the Common Lunar Lander project that NASA conducted for the Space Exploration Initiative a few years ago, or the European Space Agency's standard satellite program.  It is also not affiliated with the companies who make watches, intimate apparel, medical equipment, or program scheduling software, or several thousand Greek restaurants and other <a href="/adb/03/05/trademark-artemis.html">"Artemis" businesses</a> around the world.</P>

<P>Finally, the <a href="/artemis.html">Artemis Project</a> is not a forum for social engineering.  The project is focused on the single goal of establishing a self-supporting, permanent lunar base.  Social causes and politics are kept out of the program, except as necessary to achieve the moon base goal.</P>


