<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>1. Artemis Project Public Briefing Outline</TITLE></HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<!-- Artemis Data Book -->
<!-- ADB section 1. Project Overview -->
<!-- file: /adb/01/public-briefing-outline.html -->
<!-- Keywords: artemis project speech briefing presentation outline
overview lunar tourism vision -->
<!-- v 1.0 -->
<h2 align="center">Artemis Data Book</H2>
<h2 align="center">1. Project Overview</H2>
<h2 align="center">Artemis Project Public Briefing Outline</H2>
<P ALIGN=CENTER><I>Gregory R. Bennett</I></P>
<P><HR><P>
<ol>
<P><LI><B>Have you ever day-dreamed about traveling to another planet? You
can! We'll show you how!</B></P>

<P>[An illustration of the lunar landscape as seen from your room at the <a
href="/adv/02/07/02/01/">Luna City Hotel</a> is just what we need here. We
explain later what the viewer is looking at by repeating the image.]</P>

<P>Hit 'em right up front with the number one concept shock:</P>

<P align=CENTER><B>YOU CAN GO, TOO!</B></P>

<P><LI><B>The government isn't going to do it</B> [NASA budget image],
but...</P>

<P align="CENTER"><img src="/images/asi199600026.gif" width=230 height=165
alt="NASA Budget Graph"><P>

<P>The risk here is that seeing NASA's budget is very threatening to NASA
fans, and especially to NASA personnel. It's also very unpopular with NSS
leadership because it shows rather dramatically how effective they've been
in stumping for an expanded government space program.</P>

<P><LI><B>We can do it ourselves!</B></P>

<P>And you can be a part of it! (This, in story-telling parlance, is
called "foreshadowing the plot." Just make the claim and leave it at 
that. You'll deliver on the promise later.)</P>

<P><LI><B>The moon is the front door to the universe.</B></P>

<P>No matter what you want to do in space, the best place to start is the
moon. So we're making that first step.</P>

<P><LI><B>This is what we're doing.</B> [Reference mission]</P>

<P><li><B>This is how we pay for it.</B> [Money story]</P>

<P>Don't hit them too early with the economics. They get bored. Once they
have a solid vision in mind, then they'll be interested in how we're going
to pay for it.</P>

<P><LI><B>This is how the Artemis Project leads to YOU traveling to the
moon.</B></p>

<P align="CENTER"><img src="/images/asi199600032.gif" width=384 height=256
alt="Image of Commercial Passenger SSTO Landing on the Moon"></P>

<P>(The rockets-to-the-moon story, with the economics of <a
href="/adb/02/07/02/01/">tourism</a> in the voice-over.)</p>

<P><img align=right src="/Gifs/artlogob.gif" alt="Artemis Project
Logo"><li><B>This is how we've organized the program.</B> [Illo of the
Artemis Society, commercial companies, and spaceship builders]</P>

<P>I don't mention <a href="http://www.tlrc.com/">The Lunar Resources
Company</a> until I get to this point. A company is "something somebody
else does" while the Artemis Society is something everyone in the audience
can do.</P>

<P><li><B>This is what you can do to make it happen.</B></P>
<ul type=circle>
<li><a href="/asi_member.html">Join</a> the <a
href="/asi_index.html">Artemis Society</a>
<li>Help with ASI projects<br>
List of projects, teams, committees, local chapters
<li>Organize a <a href="/adb/07/local-chapters.html">local chapter</a>
<lI>Help spread the word
<li>Check out the web site for more detailed lists of things you can 
do.</UL></OL> <P>

