</DOCHDR>
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>1.2 Why the Artemis Project is Different</TITLE></HEAD><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><!-- Artemis Data Book --><!-- ADB section 1.2 Vision --><!-- file: /adb/01/02/artemis-is-different.html --><!-- v 1.0 --><h2 align="center">Artemis Data Book</H2><h2 align="center">1.2 Vision</H2><h2 align="center">Why the Artemis Project is Different</H2><P ALIGN=CENTER><I>Gregory R. Bennett</I></P><P><HR><P><P>There are a couple of unique aspects to the <ahref="/artemis.html">Artemis Project</a> that make this projectdifferent from what we, the body of space activism, have done before.</P><P>For one, the Artemis Project is designed to be a <ahref="/adb/03/01/revenue-breakdown.html">profit-making</a> enterprise fromthe <a href="/adb/04/01/01/01/">first launch</a>.  For two decades we'vetried wheedling the government to do it, and we've tried the beggingapproach.  That didn't work.  But we've never really tried to use theeconomic power of the entertainment industry and do it as show business.(Which is all space travel means to Joe Sixpack anyhow; and Joe is our mainaudience.)  We've even flirted with the megaprofits-in-the-long-runapproach, but business isn't set up for that kind of long run.</P><P>The other difference is that we can pump current spacecraft designexperience into the project.  Folks often leap into designing spaceshipsonly to be daunted by the detailed design work.</P><P>And finally, we have people with experience in both the commercialaerospace industry and the way the government does it.  Without experiencein both arenas, people just don't realize that spacecraft don't need to beas expensive as they are today.  All the cost models are based on thehistorical costs of space programs instead of looking at how much of thatmoney is spent on maintaining the fixed assets and infrastructure inherentin a government operation.</P><P>For emphasis: I'm not NASA-bashing.  After almost 20 years at JSC Istill don't have any great ideas how any government agency could avoidthose costs.</P><P>Actually, the Artemis Project is benefitting greatly from the work theReturn to the Moon campaign is doing.  They're knocking down politicalroadblocks that a year ago really worried us.</P><P>Incidentally, lots of times folks have suggested to me we should all gettogether behind one space project, but I disagree.  Artemis fills in aniche between the Space Access Society and Return to the Moon's lunarprospectors, and the Mars and space colonies enthusiasts.  (These are allprojects I enthusiastically support.)  I don't see any gain in spendinganother two decades trying to get organized when we're actually doing greatthe way we are.  We're finally <I>doing</i>&nbsp;something instead of justtalking about it!</P><!-- Nav Bar --><hr size="5"><table align=center border=4 cellpadding = 3 cellspacing=2><tr><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/index.html">ArtemisProject</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/asi_index.html">ArtemisSociety</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/adb/index.html">ArtemisData Book</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="/adb/j/index.html">FAQ</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="/adb/04/index.html">Reference Mission</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.tlrc.com/catalog.html">Catalog</a></b></tr></table><hr size="5"><font size=1>Copyright &#169; 1996 Artemis Society International.Updated Sat, Apr 15, 1996<br>Content by <a href="/bios/bennett.gregory.html">Gregory R. Bennett</a> <ahref="mailto:grb@asi.org">&lt;grb@asi.org&gt;</a>, maintained by <AHREF="MAILTO:simon@eagle.ca">&lt;simon@eagle.ca&gt;</A>.<br>"<a href="/Artemis.html">The Artemis Project</a>"is a trademark of <aHREF="http://www.tlrc.com/Lrc.html">The Lunar ResourcesCompany</a>.</font></body></html>
