<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//SQ//DTD HTML 2.0 HoTMetaL + extensions//EN">
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>1.2 Requirements of Moonbase Artemis</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<!-- Artemis Data Book -->
<!-- ADB section 1.2 Vision -->
<!-- file: /adb/01/02/moonbase-requirements.html
/adb/02/01/moonbase-requirements.html-->
<!-- Keywords: Artemis Project frontier vision goals commercial manned space
development company money -->
<!-- v 1.0 -->
<H2 ALIGN="center">Artemis Data Book</H2>
<H2 ALIGN="center">1.2 Vision</H2>
<H2 ALIGN="center">2.1 Expanding the Lunar Base</H2>
<H2 ALIGN="center">Requirements of Moonbase Artemis</H2>
<P></P>
<HR>
<P>

</P>
<P>Ultimately we want to see a thriving spacefaring community.  Besides
<A HREF="/adb/04/02/05/04/">digging up moon dirt</A> and <A
HREF="/adb/02/02/">separating</A>
out the good stuff, that includes <A HREF="/adb/02/06/">people living</A> on
the <A HREF="/adb/02/01">moon</A>, in <A HREF="/adb/02/06/">space</A>, on
space stations (or colonies, if they're feasible), building powersats (if
they're feasible), <A HREF="/adb/01/02/asteroid-mission-notes.html">mining
asteroids</A>, building communities on Mars, <A HREF="/adb/02/05/">exploring
the outer planets</A>, conducting exploration and scientific research in all
these environments, and doing whatever it is people want to do.</P>
<P>There are a host of options from which to choose.  The path we take in
development of a lunar base to achieve that grand vision is not well-defined.
However, we don't have to narrow down that field right now. We have sufficient
information to define the basic requirements for the core of a lunar base.  No
matter what path we take, the initial lunar base must:
</P>
<OL>
<LI><P>Support visiting crews and keep them happy and healthy
</P><UL>

<LI>We'll probably learn most of what we need to know for long-term habitation
of the moon by providing this function
</LI>
</UL></LI>
<LI><P>Be indefinitely maintainable
</P></LI>
<LI><P>Have an open architecture for upgrades to any system
</P><UL>

<LI>We'll want to close the <A
HREF="/adb/04/03/05/consumable-reduction.html">life
support loop</A> as quickly as we can to reduce resupply requirements   </LI>
<LI>If computer systems continue to become obsolescent as they are doing now,
we might be replacing large chunks of the electronics on every flight
</LI>
</UL></LI>
<LI><P>Support <A HREF="/adb/04/03/08/">lunar surface EVA</A>
</P></LI>
<LI><P>Provide power, data, communications, and <A HREF="/adb/02/05/">life
support</A> for the crew
</P></LI>
<LI><P>Support <A HREF="/adb/02/02/">regolith mining</A>
</P></LI>
<LI><P>Support exploitation of in-situ material
</P><UL>

<LI><A HREF="/adb/04/03/10/04/">Oxygen extraction</A>, at least as a
leveraging factor for future flights to and from the moon   </LI>
<LI>Metals extraction, to capitalize on the mass that's there
</LI>
</UL></LI>
<LI><P>Support space traffic to and from the moon
</P><UL>

<LI>Landing sites   </LI>
<LI>Landing support systems, such as radio beacons   </LI>
<LI>Navigation systems; perhaps several radio beacons on the surface
</LI>
</UL></LI>
<LI><P>Support industrial processes on the moon
</P><UL>

<LI>Storage and garages for external equipment
</LI>
</UL></LI>
<LI><P>Look neat</P>
</LI>
</OL>
<P>Exactly what the external equipment will be depends on what we learn along
the way.  If we can afford it, or if we need a large population on the moon
right away, we might put priority on searching for a big cavern where we can
establish a large, permanent community.  Alternatively, if we can automate a lot
of the processing and have customers for <A HREF="/adb/04/03/10/04/">lunar
oxygen</A>, we'll want to put our priorities on those industrial processes and a
launch system to get payloads off the moon.</P>
<!-- Nav Bar -->
<HR SIZE="5">
