<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>2. Interplanetary Trade on the Moon</TITLE></HEAD><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><!-- Artemis Data Book --><!-- ADB section 2. Scenarios for Manned Space Development --><!-- file: /adb/02/trade.html --><!-- Keywords: legal issues ocean law sea lunar resources international lawUN political roadblocks --><!-- v 1.0 --><h2 align="center">Artemis Data Book</H2><h2 align="center">2. Scenarios for Manned Space Development</H2><h2 align="center">Interplanetary Trade on the Moon</H2><P align=center><I>Jim Davidson</I></P><P><HR><P><P>The Moon will not be self-sufficient for a long time.Indeed, a good case can be made that it will never be self-sufficient.The United States is not, today, self-sufficient.  If one looks at thebalance of payments or our balance of trade, it is the world's largestdebtor nation.</P><P>Then what does self-sufficiency mean?  Is it true that no man is anisland?  Thus,none of us are truly self-sufficient.</P><P>There is obviously an implication that the Moon will be more thansomewhat dependent on resources from Earth.  I wonder, however, if that is true.The Moon is large enough to be considered an 8th continent of Earth.  The Apollomissions surveyed 6 widely separated sites on the near side, and Russiareturned samples from another two near side sites.  Hardly a basis for aglobal analysis of resource dependency.</P><P>If there is water-ice near the poles and if significant carbonaceouschondriteimpact sites can be identified, there is no reason the "necessities" couldn't besupplied from indigenous resources.  Not right away, but quite soon.  Clearlythere is oxygen, aluminum, iron, and silicon for all our needs.  If water iceand carbonaceous chondrites are scarce, these can be found in Earth-crossingasteroids and a variety of other sites in the Solar System.  The ability toreach the Moon and settle there implies the ability to reach Earth crossingasteroids and most other places in the Solar System.</P><P>Will the Moon be dependent on trade?  Yes, forever.  Trade with theUS? No.  Trade with Earth?  Probably.  Trade with other places in the SolarSystem? Certainly.  Will the Moon have anything that it can trade?Yes, or we wouldn't go there.  Tourism, mineral wealth, free banking,information industries, farside radio astronomy, and perhaps low gravity orvacuum-related industries are among the possibilities.  It wouldn't besurprisingif agricultural products were eventually exported to other spacesettlements.</P><P>Meanwhile, the Moon will always be uphill from the Earth to a much greaterextent (20:1 in terms of energy) than the Earth is uphill from the Moon.  Theability to launch items from the surface of the Moon is an essential element ofeconomic infrastructure.</P><!-- Nav Bar --><hr size="5"><table align=center border=4 cellpadding = 3 cellspacing=2><tr><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/index.html">ArtemisProject</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/asi_index.html">ArtemisSociety</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/adb/index.html">ArtemisData Book</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="/adb/j/index.html">FAQ</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="/adb/04/index.html">Reference Mission</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.tlrc.com/catalog.html">Catalog</a></b></tr></table><hr size="5"><font size=1>Copyright &#169; 1996 Artemis Society International.Updated Thu, Apr 4, 1996<br>Content by Jim Davidson <ahref="mailto:73370.3046@compuserve.com">&lt;73370.3046@compuserve.com&gt;</a>, maintained by <AHREF="MAILTO:simon@eagle.ca">&lt;simon@eagle.ca&gt;</A>.<br>"<a href="/Artemis.html">The Artemis Project</a>"is a trademark of <aHREF="http://www.tlrc.com/Lrc.html">The Lunar Resources Company</a>.</font></body></html>
