<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>2.1. Economics of the Permanent LunarCommunity</TITLE></HEAD><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><!-- Artemis Data Book --><!-- ADB section 2.1. Expanding the Lunar Base  --><!-- file: /adb/02/01/lunar-community-econ.html --><!-- v 1.0 --><h2 align="center">Artemis Data Book</H2><h2 align="center">2.1. Expanding the Lunar Base</H2><h2 align="center">Economics of the Permanent Lunar Community</H2><P ALIGN=CENTER><I>Gregory R. Bennett</I></P><P><HR><P><P>One of the focus points of the Artemis Project's long-range vision is aself-supporting lunar community, where people can emigrate and visit. Asignificant fraction of the population would be able to liquidate theirterrestrial assets, move to the Moon, and buy an apartment built with lunarmaterials.<P>The <a href="/adb/06/07/02/01/01/">Advanced Planning TechnicalCommittee</a> has just begun work on an economic model for the lunarcommunity.  The lunar community -- that is, the permanent residents -- willearn their living either by exploiting the resources of the moon (includingtourism) or through occupations which can telecommute to do business onEarth.</P><P>On the ASI website, there's a <a href="/adb/02/07/02/01/">description</a> ofthe size of the staff and supporting industries required for lunar tourismto happen.  Presumably, those people are permanent or at least long-termresidents.  In addition to that, the lunar resources industries -- <ahref="/adb/04/03/10/04/oxygen-extraction.html">oxygen</a>, <ahref="/adb/02/02/">metals</a>, volatiles -- will need a lot ofemployees.</P><P>In addition to directly exploiting the moon's resources, however, thelunar community can enjoy a significant advantage from people who want tolive there just because it's a nifty place to live.  Many occupations whichexist on Earth today could be done from the moon -- if you can do it on theInternet, you can do it on the moon.</P><P>We should enthusiastically encourage telecommuting from the moonbecause those permanent residents will be creating wealth on Earth owned bypermanent residents of the moon.  That significantly enhances the economyof the lunar community by creating a positive balance of payments.</P><!-- Nav Bar --><hr size="5"><table align=center border=4 cellpadding = 3 cellspacing=2><tr><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/index.html">ArtemisProject</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/asi_index.html">ArtemisSociety</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/adb/index.html">ArtemisData Book</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="/adb/j/index.html">FAQ</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="/adb/04/index.html">Reference Mission</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.tlrc.com/catalog.html">Catalog</a></b></tr></table><hr size="5"><font size=1>Copyright &#169; 1996 Artemis Society International.Updated Fri, July 19, 1996<br>Content by <a href="/bios/bennett.gregory.html">Gregory R. Bennett</a> <ahref="mailto:grb@asi.org">&lt;grb@asi.org&gt;</a>, maintained by <AHREF="MAILTO:simon@eagle.ca">&lt;simon@eagle.ca&gt;</A>.<br>"<a href="/Artemis.html">The Artemis Project</a>"is a trademark of <aHREF="http://www.tlrc.com/Lrc.html">The Lunar ResourcesCompany</a>.</font></body></html>
