<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>2.1 Sintering Roads with Solar Power</TITLE></HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<!-- Artemis Data Book -->
<!-- ADB section 2.1 Expanding the Lunar Base -->
<!-- file: /adb/02/01/sintering-roads.html -->
<!-- v 1.0 -->
<h2 align="center">Artemis Data Book</H2>
<h2 align="center">2.1 Expanding the Lunar Base</H2>
<h2 align="center">Sintering Roads with Solar Power</H2>
<P ALIGN=CENTER><I>Simon Rowland</I></P>
<P><HR><P>

<P>In 1988, a paper titled "Enabling Lunar and Space Missions by Laser Power
Transmission" was published by R.J. DeYoung, J.E.N ealy, D.H. Humes, and
W.E. Meador of NASA's Langely Research Center in Hampton, Virginia. Among
the proposals from DeYoung, et al., is to use a high-intensity laser beam
to heat the lunar surface to the melting point, presumably from orbit.
When it cools, we'll have a hard, glassy surface for roadways and launch
pads.</P>

<P>A 1 megawatt laser heating a 1-meter diameter spot for 10 minutes will
melt the regolith to a depth of 2 cm.</P>

<P>Although superficially this concept seems unfeasible by the level of
infrastructure required to laser-sinter the roads, a simple inflatable
reflector could serve a similar purpose. With solar radiation at 1.4 KW per
square meter, a 13-meter radius inflatable reflector could be driven along
at 3.8 m/h, and make a road 1.5 meters wide as it goes. This could make 4
km of roads near the lunar habitat in four months before the second misson,
and a 40 meter square landing pad to boot.</P>

<P>Sintering roads and walkways will be important for increasing the
efficiency of ground transportation, and reducing <a
href="/adb/m/03/04/">problems with fines</a> (moondust), which are
anticipated to be a major issue for a permanent lunar habitat.</P>

<!-- Nav Bar -->
<hr size="5">
