<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>4.1.1.3 Lunar Resources Distribution</TITLE></HEAD><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><!-- Artemis Data Book --><!-- ADB section 2.2 Lunar Mining 4.1.1.3 Site Selection --><!-- file: /adb/02/02/resource-distribution.html/adb/04/01/01/03/resource-distribution.html --><!-- Keywords: lunar resources moon landing site selection minerals impactgeology selenology --><!-- v 1.0 --><h2 align="center">Artemis Data Book</H2><h2 align="center">2.2 Lunar Mining</H2><h2 align="center">4.1.1.3 Site Selection</H2><h2 align="center">Lunar Resources Distribution</H2><I><P ALIGN=CENTER>Bryce Walden</P></I><P><HR><P><P>Suggestions that discussion on the origins of craters and 'seas' (maria)on the Moon are trivial or off-topic are missing the point. The <ahref="/artemis.html">Artemis Project</a> will have to do everything it canto assure its <a href="/adb/04/">first mission</a> pays off. Among otherthings, this means locating at a lunar position with the highestmineralogical payoff for our purposes. In order to find the most promisingsites, we need to understand the underlying dynamics of lunar minerologicaldisposition. We don't want to land just anywhere, or only on the mostsmooth ground. Location of <a href="/adb/04/01/01/03/">lunar landingsites</a> is at least as important as any other profit-related decisionArtemis Project will have to make.</P><P>Data from Clementine, Lunar Prospector, even the Galileo flyby arehelpful for finding the most superficial mineralogical features, and makingprecise surface maps. Data from these probes and analysis of Apollo-erafindings help us determine the history of the Moon, the nature of lunardifferentiation, and the placement of strategic <ahref="/adb/02/02/">resources</a>.</P><P>To suggest early lunar bombardment was preferentially on the "leadingedge" is technically probably correct, but most writers here appear to ignorethe high probability that the early Moon was not yet tidally-locked to Earthand spun on its axis faster than it does today. There does seem to be apreferential equatorial broad "band" of basin-forming impacts, with somesigns of another band at an angle to the first, indicating the Moon mayhave made a major change in its axis of rotation. This could haveimplications for the locations of resources.</P><!-- Nav Bar --><hr size="5"><table align=center border=4 cellpadding = 3 cellspacing=2><tr><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/index.html">ArtemisProject</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/asi_index.html">ArtemisSociety</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/adb/index.html">ArtemisData Book</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="/adb/j/index.html">FAQ</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="/adb/04/index.html">Reference Mission</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.tlrc.com/catalog.html">Catalog</a></b></tr></table><hr size="5"><font size=-2>Copyright &#169; 1996 Artemis Society International.Updated Sun, Arp 7, 1996<br>Content by Bryce Waldin <ahref="mailto:bwalden@aol.com">&lt;bwalden@aol.com&gt;</a>, maintained by <AHREF="MAILTO:simon@eagle.ca">&lt;simon@eagle.ca&gt;</A>.<br>"<a href="/Artemis.html">The Artemis Project</a>"is a trademark of <aHREF="http://www.tlrc.com/Lrc.html">The Lunar Resources Company</a>.</font></body></html>
