<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>2.7.1.1 LEO Stockpiling of Lunar Voyage Fuel</TITLE></HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<!-- Artemis Data Book -->
<!-- ADB section 2.7.1.1 Multiple-Vehicles Scenario -->
<!-- file: /adb/02/07/01/01/leo-fuel-stockpile.html -->
<!-- Keywords: ssto fuel earth lunar oxygen mass leo refueling  -->
<!-- v 1.0 -->
<h2 align="center">Artemis Data Book</H2>
<h2 align="center">2.7.1.1 Multiple-Vehicles Scenario</H2>
<h2 align="center">LEO Stockpiling of Lunar Voyage Fuel</H2>
<P ALIGN=CENTER><I>Gregory R. Bennett</I></P>
<P><HR><P>

<P>The primary drawback to using many SSTO rockets to stockpile fuel in
Earth orbit is the number of flights required.</P>

<P>Suppose the useful load of an SSTO is 5% of its gross lift-off weight,
and its mass ratio is 90%. (That's optimistic, but it demonstrates the 
point.) Then, to completely refuel the rocket in LEO, we would need 18
flights to carry fuel tanks to orbit, and then one more to launch the one
we're going to send to the moon.</P>

<P>Now, using the preliminary numbers for the proposed <a
href="/adb/04/02/07/01/02/business-plan.html">commercial SSTO</a>, each
launch costs us about $4 million. So those 19 launches would cost $76
million. That means our cost per passenger (assuming 50 paying passengers)
would be $1.52 million, which is a tad higher than the $96,000 we were
shooting for.</P>

<P>Hence, the argument that we should develop the <a
href="/adb/04/03/10/04/oxygen-extraction.html">lunar fuels</a> industry
first, and then open a gas station in LEO. We're using lunar resources as
a leveraging technology, and its a really useful lever!</P>



<!-- Nav Bar -->
