<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>3. About The Lunar Resources Company</TITLE></HEAD><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><!-- Artemis Data Book --><!-- ADB section 3. Business of the Artemis Project --><!-- file: /adb/03/about-tlrc.html --><!-- Keywords: money investment stock shares funding business investingboard of directors --><!-- v 1.0 --><h2 align="center">Artemis Data Book</H2><h2 align="center">3. Business of the Artemis Project</H2><h2 align="center">About The Lunar Resources Company</H2><I><P ALIGN=CENTER>Gregory Bennett</P></I><P><HR><P><P>We've received several inquiries about investing in <ahref="http://www.tlrc.com/">The Lunar ResourcesCompany</a>.</P><P>Right now we're puzzling out detailed business plans so we can figure out howmuch capital we'll need, and when.  Based on that information, we'll be ableto write private offering letters, offering stock to get things going in allthese different industries.  We plan separate offerings in each major field ofthe entertainment industry because that will make it more clear to potentialinvestors what we're planning.  Some folks are experts in <ahref="http://www.tlrc.com/artemis_mag.hmtl">publications</a>, othersin merchandising, etc., so we'll set it up so someone can invest in just onearea if he prefers.</P><P>At the same time we're developing the background scripts ("the bible") forstories set in the <a href="/artemis.html">Artemis Project</a> milieu.  Wehave to do that to provide a consistent set of entertainment products andstories to go with them.  We want to make sure we're doing top quality workin sharing this adventure.</P><P>Emphasis: This is not a stock offering or a solicitation to sell stock. SECregulations are strict.  For a private offering, stock can only be sold viapersonal contact to individuals who are personally familiar with the principalofficers of the company.  Investors also must be in a financial position tolose whatever they invest.  We also need to make sure we comply with the lawsof each investor's home state or province.  The rules require a bit ofpaperwork and some lawyers' time.  There will be non-disclosure agreements andinvestor suitability forms to sign.  It's still lots less expensive thanspending a million dollars on an initial public offering.  If you are thinkingof investing in The Lunar Resources Company, please do wait for the offeringletter and study it thoroughly before making a decision.</P><P>The regulations are vague about what it means to know someone personally.  Iwould interpret this to mean you're familiar enough with the individuals onthe board of directors to know whether to trust their judgment and evaluatetheir ability to run the business. We don't think you can make that kind ofjudgment based solely on meeting someone in the electronic world or seeingone of our television interviews.  You'd need to meet at least one of themembers of the board of directors close enough to shake his hand and find outwhat he's really made of.</P><P>Incidentally, the Lunar Resources board of directors currently consistsof:</P><UL type=circle><LI>Gregory Bennett (League City, Texas)<LI>Dana Carson (Pasadena, Maryland)<LI>Kevin O'Donnell (Campbell, California)<LI>Howard Slade (Friendswood, Texas)<LI>Ian Randal Strock (Brooklyn, New York)</UL><P>Our best guess is that we're still a couple months away from an offering.This is a <I>very</I> complex business, and growing more complex each day.</P><P>In the meantime, we could use some feedback.  If you might be interested ininvesting in this business, would you want to buy stock in one area of thecompany, or the whole thing?  Folks reading Artemis-list are familiar with theconcept and space travel in general, but other investors are not; so we willoffer stock in several individual business units.  That shopping list, in theorder in which we expect we'll be doing offerings:</P><ul type=square><LI>Publishing<li>Software<LI>Merchandising<LI>Games<LI>Retailing (including an Internet store and mail-order catalog)<LI>Simulations and Virtual Reality<LI>Motion Pictures and Television (which might be separated)<LI>Space Flight</UL><P>The order of that list gives you some insight into our approach -- thecommercial businesses will earn the income to finance the initial spaceflight.  If the lunar base pays off as it should, it will become theoverwhelming producer of income; but remember that from a business standpoint,we are sailing into unknown seas.</P><P>We also could use names for each of these business units.  Ideas are mostwelcome!  There are many businesses out there already using the <ahref="/adb/03/05/trademark-artemis.html">name "Artemis"</a>so we'll probably avoid using that moniker for anything except the Project asa whole, and of course the <a href="/asi_index.html">Artemis Society</a>.</P><!-- Nav Bar --><hr size="5"><table align=center border=4 cellpadding = 3 cellspacing=2><tr><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/index.html">ArtemisProject</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/asi_index.html">ArtemisSociety</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/adb/index.html">ArtemisData Book</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="/adb/j/index.html">FAQ</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="/adb/04/index.html">Reference Mission</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.tlrc.com/catalog.html">Catalog</a></b></tr></table><hr size="5"><font size=-2>Copyright &#169; 1996 Artemis Society International.Updated Mon, Aug 26, 1996<br>Content by <a href="/bios/bennett.gregory.html">Gregory R. Bennett</a> <ahref="mailto:grb@asi.org">&lt;grb@asi.org&gt;</a>, maintained by <AHREF="MAILTO:simon@eagle.ca">&lt;simon@eagle.ca&gt;</A>.<br>"<a href="/Artemis.html">The Artemis Project</a>"is a trademark of <aHREF="http://www.tlrc.com/Lrc.html">The Lunar Resources Company</a>.</font></body></html>
