<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>3. Spaceship Building Credentials</TITLE></HEAD><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><!-- Artemis Data Book section 3. Business of the Artemis Project --><!-- file: /adb/03/spacecraft-credentials.html --><!-- Keywords: risks descent stage dead man's curve abort ascent stagelanding gear burn braking --><!-- v 1.0 --><h2 align="center">Artemis Data Book</H2><h2 align="center">3. Business of the Artemis Project</H2><h2 align="center">Spaceship Building Credentials</H2><P><HR><P><P>In addition to the considerable professional talent volunteering theirtime to get the project off top dead center, our plan is to contract detaileddevelopment of the spacecraft to an experienced spaceship builder, a company with aproven track record which has the expertise and processes in place to do thejob right.  We can't announce publicly which aerospace companies are doingwhat because those decisions haven't been made yet; each one will take acorporate commitment from the top down.</P><P>There are no secrets about who we've been talking to about these things,though, as long as we emphasize that it's in the talking-about stage and notin the contract-negotiating stage.  First off the block is Carnegie-MellonUniversity and the <ahref="http://www.cs.cmu.edu/afs/cs/project/lri-3/www/moon-bug.html">rovingrobots</a>.  We've also discussed the rovers and where wemight go with this project with David Gump of <ahref="http://www.lunacorp.com/">LunaCorp</a>.  We're talking to<a href="http://hvsun4.mdc.com/SPACEHAB/SPACEHAB.html">Spacehab</a>, Inc.and McDonnell Douglas (Huntsville) about the pressurizedelements.  We're talking to VIGA Tech, formed from a group of fellows atSandia National Laboratories, about VR simulations.  At McDonnell Douglas inHouston, the Lunar Base Development Team has just started looking at themission design and spacecraft architecture.  Rocket engine data are comingfrom several aerospace companies.  The key officers of <ahref="/asi_index.html">Artemis Society International</a> are NASA engineersat the Marshall Space Flight Center in Huntsville.</P><P>We've also talked to spacecraft engineers from Lockheed-Martin, Grumman,Rockwell Space Operations, Boeing Huntsville, Boeing Seattle, RocketdyneCanoga Park, McDonnell Douglas Huntington Beach, and of course NASA-JSC andthe astronaut corps.  Don't let us over-sell that point, however; it's by nomeans a coordinated effort and we can't claim to have corporate commitmentfrom any of those companies.  We'll get there, but we're not there yet.</P><P>This will take time.  For some experienced spaceship builders, theswitch to private manned space flight is severe concept shock.  Socializedspace flight is the only paradigm they know.  Don't underestimate theimportance of this barrier to entry into the field: there has been only onesuccessful pioneer in this area so far, and that's Spacehab.</P><P>Here's what's up.  While you're working on putting the project togetherand building the team (and an audience), I'm putting together the part of theproject where we need to bring in the seasoned professionals.  Within a coupleof years we're going to get to the point where we need the guys with the bigstructural analysis models and the milling machines and the bookshelves fullof data on fasteners and metals and industrial processes.  Even before then,we need the advice of the spaceship builders to avoid following fruitlesspaths, and we need their commitment to make the whole program credible.</P><!-- Nav Bar --><hr size="5"><table align=center border=4 cellpadding = 3 cellspacing=2><tr><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/index.html">ArtemisProject</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/asi_index.html">ArtemisSociety</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/adb/index.html">ArtemisData Book</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="/adb/j/index.html">FAQ</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="/adb/04/index.html">Reference Mission</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.tlrc.com/catalog.html">Catalog</a></b></tr></table><hr size="5"><font size=-2>Copyright &#169; 1996 Artemis Society International.Updated Sun, March 31, 1996<br>Content by <a href="/bios/bennett.gregory.html">Gregory R. Bennett</a> <ahref="mailto:grb@asi.org">&lt;grb@asi.org&gt;</a>, maintained by <AHREF="MAILTO:simon@eagle.ca">&lt;simon@eagle.ca&gt;</A>.<br>"<a href="/Artemis.html">The Artemis Project</a>"is a trademark of <aHREF="http://www.tlrc.com/Lrc.html">The Lunar Resources Company</a>.</font></body></html>
