<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>3. Long-term TLRC Financing</TITLE></HEAD><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><!-- Artemis Data Book --><!-- ADB section 3. Business of the Artemis Project --><!-- file: /adb/03/tlrc-long-term-financing.html --><!-- v 1.0 --><h2 align="center">Artemis Data Book</H2><h2 align="center">3. Business of the Artemis Project</H2><h2 align="center">Long-term TLRC Financing</H2><P ALIGN=CENTER><I>Gregory R. Bennett</I></P><P><HR><P><P>It is difficult to make a straightforward way to guarantee that thestockholders willnever abandon the project before the lunar flight, or that they won't abandonthe project after the first flight.  The best defense we know is assure thatcontrolling interest in the company is held by people whose primary motivationis the altruistic desire to conduct manned space flight.</P><P>However, there are two important reasons that we need to consider thefinancialmotivation for continuing the space flight:</P><ol><LI>As a publicly held company, we are bound to do what is in the bestfinancial interest of the stockholders.<P><LI>There is the risk that in the future controlling interest could fallinto the hands of people whose primary motivation is financial gain, regardlessof the means.  This could happen through a corporate take-over, despite ourbest efforts to ensure against it; or it could happen through inheritance.(Suppose, for instance, a plane crashed with a majority of our board ofdirectors, and our relatives saw only dollar signs when they inherited thestock.)</ol><P>The way the project is set up, it's in the best financial interest of thestockholders to continue development of manned spaceflight, both for the shortterm and the long term.</P><P>In the short term, the big publicity comes from the manned flight, maximizingprofit on sales of movie tickets and sundry hard goods.  The project needs verypositive publicity to succeed, and that means continuing to demonstrate that<a href="http://www.tlrc.com">The Lunar Resources Company</a> is activelypursing the dream of space development and space flight for everyone whowants to go.</P><P>Entertainment relies on volume sales, and volume sales come from publicity.The potential revenues go up by at least an order of magnitude for the firstcouple years after the flight, and will be sustained at a high level if lunardevelopment continues.  If at any time the company abandons the project, theydrop back to being just another movie-and-marketing firm, with a tremendousamount of negative publicity.</P><P.In the long term, the total profit from the projects ephemeral entertainmentvalue is trivial compared to the economic value of:</P><ul type=square><li><a href="/adb/04/03/10/04/oxygen-extraction.html">lunar oxygen</a> forrocket oxydizer above low Earth orbit<li><a href="/adb/02/09/he3-intro.html">helium 3</a> for energy productionon Earth<li>solar energy transmitted from the moon<li><a href="/adb/03/03/">scientific data</a>, both lunar and astronomical<li>lunar material for spacecraft construction<li><a href="/adb/02/07/lunacity-hotel.html">space tourism</a>, includingzero-g facilities in Earth orbit and habitations on the moon<li>use of the moon as a <a href="/adb/02/10/">launching</a> platform for<a href="/adb/02/05/">interplanetary flight</a><li>extraterrestrial real estate for permanent emigrants from Earth</ul><P>Furthermore, the economics of this business encourage continuous, vigorousdevelopment and exploitation of lunar resources.  If the stockholdersdecide to slow things down, the company will lose its market advantage.Already, several Japanese companies are poised and ready to leap into thegap.  It's important toremember that although nobody is doing it exactly the way we have proposed andthe only U.S. firm engaged in similar business is LunaCorp (the folks with theLunarTrek Rover), we are not completely free of competition.</P><P>Slowing down also means loss of public interest.  This is what happened toApollo.  When it became obvious that the program was dead-ended and that therewas no path to the average person being able to go into space, people lostinterest in the program.  We can blame the news media for dropping the ball,but they were just the carriers of the bad news.  Apollo wasn't promisinganything new after the first landing, just repetitions of the same.  The newsmedia might be condemned for their laziness and ignorance of theimportance of subsequent Apollo flights, but the real blame lies solely on theshoulders of the government officials who lead them into that situation.</P><P>All of which adds up to a conviction that <ahref="http://www.tlrc.com/">The Lunar Resources Company</a> willnever abandon manned space flight simply because it's in the company's bestinterest to continue.  The challenge to us is to document this carefully andmake sure every director of the corporation understands and agrees with it.  Aslong as I'm the boss, there is no way anyone will be employed by thecompany, either as a direct employee or contract labor, unless he understandsand agrees with what we're doing.</P><P>That even includes our lawyers and accountants.  Right now there is nobodyworking on The Artemis Project who hasn't personally expressed to me a stronginterest in developing the moon, and an understanding and belief in the projectand the way we're approaching it.</P><!-- Nav Bar --><hr size="5"><table align=center border=4 cellpadding = 3 cellspacing=2><tr><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/index.html">ArtemisProject</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/asi_index.html">ArtemisSociety</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/adb/index.html">ArtemisData Book</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="/adb/j/index.html">FAQ</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="/adb/04/index.html">Reference Mission</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.tlrc.com/catalog.html">Catalog</a></b></tr></table><hr size="5"><font size=1>Copyright &#169; 1996 Artemis Society International.Updated Sat, Apr 15, 1996<br>Content by <a href="/bios/bennett.gregory.html">Gregory R. Bennett</a> <ahref="mailto:grb@asi.org">&lt;grb@asi.org&gt;</a>, maintained by <AHREF="MAILTO:simon@eagle.ca">&lt;simon@eagle.ca&gt;</A>.<br>"<a href="/Artemis.html">The Artemis Project</a>"is a trademark of <aHREF="http://www.tlrc.com/Lrc.html">The Lunar ResourcesCompany</a>.</font></body></html>
