</DOCHDR>
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>3.2 Apollo Spaceship Development CostComparison</TITLE></HEAD><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><!-- Artemis Data Book section 3.2 Cost Analysis --><!-- file: /adb/03/02/apollo-dev-cost-comparison.html --><!-- Keywords: apollo development cost comparison simulator anecdote geminisimulator spaceship engineering cost model financial model --><!-- v 1.5 --><h2 align="center">Artemis Data Book</H2><h2 align="center">3.2 Cost Analysis</H2><h2 align="center">Apollo Spaceship Development Cost Comparison</H2><P><HR><P><P>It is often pointed out that building an engineering development <ahref="/adb/03/02/">cost model</a> based on the Apollo era doesn't make anysense because the whole environment is different today.</P><P>Back in the days of Gemini and <a href="/adb/m/02/07/">Apollo</a>, allbut a minuscule fraction of theengineering hours were spent doing the drudge work.  Here's a great example:</P><P>In the days of yore, McDonnell Douglas built an engineering simulator of theGemini electrical system.  Each Gemini spacecraft was a little different, sothey had to make a math model of each ship, and keep the math model updated. That meant lots of changes.</P><P>The math models were stored on punched paper tape.  (The hottest storagedevicearound back then was the magnetic drum.)  Engineers would work out the mathmodel and fill out a form, and a team of keypunch operators would punch thetapes.  They didn't have a way to duplicate or edit these tapes; to make achange, they had to start all over with a new tape, keypunching every bite byhand.  When a tape was done, the operator would make a printout, and theengineers would painstakingly go through the whole thing looking for errors. If they found an error, the operator had to start all over again.</P><P>The great joyous moment for the electrical system simulator team was the daythey finally convinced NASA to let them acquire a teletype machine that couldnot only punch paper tapes, but also duplicate them.</P><P>Imagine the amount of human effort that went into the function youperform today every time you smack that backspace key.  And remember that 100%of the cost of everything is human effort.</P><!-- Nav Bar --><hr size="5"><table align=center border=4 cellpadding = 3 cellspacing=2><tr><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/index.html">ArtemisProject</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/asi_index.html">ArtemisSociety</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/adb/index.html">ArtemisData Book</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="/adb/j/index.html">FAQ</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="/adb/04/index.html">Reference Mission</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.tlrc.com/catalog.html">Catalog</a></b></tr></table><hr size="5"><font size=1>Copyright &#169; 1996 Artemis Society International.Updated Sun, Apr 14, 1996<br>Content by <a href="/bios/bennett.gregory.html">Gregory R. Bennett</a> <ahref="mailto:grb@asi.org">&lt;grb@asi.org&gt;</a>, maintained by <AHREF="MAILTO:simon@eagle.ca">&lt;simon@eagle.ca&gt;</A>.<br>"<a href="/Artemis.html">The Artemis Project</a>"is a trademark of <aHREF="http://www.tlrc.com/Lrc.html">The Lunar Resources Company</a>.</font></body></html>
