<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>3.3 Direct Investment in Manned Space</TITLE></HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<!-- Artemis Data Book -->
<!-- ADB section 3.3 Financing the Project -->
<!-- file: /adb/03/03/direct-investment.html -->
<!-- Keywords: funding investment stocks shares investors lunar resources
company resources revenues return on investment ROI money story -->
<!-- v 1.0 -->
<h2 align="center">Artemis Data Book</H2>
<h2 align="center">3.3 Financing the Project</H2>
<h2 align="center">Direct Investment in Manned Space</H2>
<P ALIGN=CENTER><I>Gregory R. Bennett</I></P>
<P><HR><P>

<P>We've structured the <a href="/artemis.html">Artemis Project</a> to
avoid having to ask people to
<a href="/adb/03/03/direct-investment-chunnel.html">invest directly</a> in
the space flight because attempts to get private funding
for manned space flight have not been successful in the past.  Twenty years
(since 1976) of zero success provides a pretty strong body of empirical
data.  That doesn't mean it's impossible; but it does indicate that the
chances of success are very small.</P>

<P>Until we have an operational lunar base which has proved out the habitation
systems, lunar mining, and basic feasibility of the transportation system,
we won't know enough about the risks to even begin to assess them.  Once
those things have happened, we will be able to show a long-range business
plan that shows how <a href="/adb/03/03/long-term-resources.html">lunar
resources can be profitably exploited.  In the
long run, the strongest source of income for a lunar community will
probably be <a href="/adb/02/07/lunacity-hotel.html">tourism</a>.  Second
would be <a href="/adb/04/03/10/04/">lunar oxygen</a> for <a
href="/adb/02/07/ssto-business-plan.html">rocket fuel</a>.  (This
assumes the <a href="/adb/02/09/">helium-3</a> scenario doesn't happen.
We're ambivalent about that
one.)</P>

<P>We have two main problems with getting to the point where we can ask people
to invest directly in manned space flight: (1) concept of manned space as
an unprofitable government venture, and (2) level of risk vs. the time it
takes to break even.</P>

<P>Because of the Apollo Program and successors, people have developed a
mind-set that manned space must be so large and complex that only a huge
government body could do it; and that the only reason it's worth doing is
to pull off a political stunt.  This is clearly not true of you, or you
wouldn't be reading this; however it is certainly true of the great
majority of the world's population.</P>

<P>It's also true of the great majority of people working on space programs
today.  If you survey the web sites, especially the NASA, NSS, and SEDS
sites, you'll see that nearly all the activity is geared toward convincing
the U.S. government to do something.  (It ain't gonna happen.  For
evidence, review the history of NASA's budget, appearing soon on a web site
near you.)<P>

<P>Manned space as commercial enterprise is too speculative an idea for most
large investors.  The length of time between the initial investment and
assurance of return on that investment is too great to justify the risks.
Investors need some data upon which to base an investment decision.  When we
wrote the <a href="/artemis.html">Artemis Project goal</A> "to bootstrap
private enterprise into manned
space flight," that's exactly what we had in mind.  Establish a proven track
record, and the world will beat a path to the moon.</P>

<P><hr width=30%><P>

<P>As to about whether <a href="http://www.tlrc.com/">LRC</a> would accept
a deal from a large
company wanting to investing directly in the manned space flight:  All
caveats and concerns aside, of course we would.</P>

<P>Specifically whether we'd accept that deal from Mitsubishi: I dunno.  We
don't know the details of what MHI and LunaCorp have agreed to.  However,
the folks we've met from both these corporations are really sharp, so we can
assume they've worked out a win-win situation; and if they succeed, we all
win.  Of course, LRC isn't looking at the same product lines as <a
href="http://www.lunacorp.com/">LunaCorp</a>.</P>

<P>We haven't even considered a robotic rover as a <a
href="http://www.tlrc.com/">Lunar Resources Company</a>
product line.  That's not because we wouldn't want to do this, but because
there are at least three strong candidates for suppliers: LunaCorp (with
Carnegie-Mellon), International Space Enterprises, and McDonnell Douglas.
The same is true of the manned element for the
reference mission, but if LRC were to bid against MDC for the manned
element, it'd make sense stick with MDC.  And MDC isn't the only spaceship
builder on the
block.<a href="#note">*</a>  In business parlance, there are significant
barriers to entry in
those two fields.</P>

<P>Similarly, when the question of producing CD-ROMs came up, my first
thought was to contact LunaCorp.  That's an easy make-or-buy decision: they
know this business; we (LRC) don't.  This might be a better example in
going out for investors.  It will be lots easier to develop a business plan
with an experienced producer and marketer of CD-ROMs.  We can show
investors the track record that LunaCorp has built.  On the other hand, the
<a href="/artemis.html">Artemis Project</a> can provide some cool content
and market appeal which would
otherwise not be available to <a
href="http://www.lunacorp.com/">LunaCorp</a>'s CD-ROM product line.  Again,
everybody wins.</P>

<P><hr width=30%><P>

<P>The proposed robotic <a href="/adb/05/05/">lunar sample return
mission</a> is a different story.  
We're talking about a much lower level of capital, earlier return on
investment, and less risk.  If <a
href="http://www.lunacorp.com/">LunaCorp+CMU</a> succeed, there will be an
established precedent for missions like this.  That gives us a solid basis
for an offering to investors.  The big unknown will be returning the
material to Earth.  It has been done, but never as private enterprise.  We'd
feel much more comfortable asking people to invest directly in the lunar
sample return than we would with the manned lunar base.</P>

<P>Now, all that said, if there appears to be sufficient interest, we will go
ahead with an offering which allows people to invest directly in the lunar
community.  We might not be able to raise enough capital to do the whole
program that way, but if enough people want to do this, we'll get there
that much faster.  There's always the chance that we'll be pleasantly
surprised!</P>

<!-- Nav Bar -->
<hr size="5">
<table align=center border=4 cellpadding = 3 cellspacing=2><tr>
