<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>3.3 Investment in the Lunar Resources Company</TITLE></HEAD><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><!-- Artemis Data Book --><!-- ADB section 3.3 Financing the Project --><!-- file: /adb/03/03/investing-tlrc-1.html --><!-- Keywords: habitat robot Carnegie-Mellon University Lunacorp regolithheat insulation bury --><!-- v 1.0 --><h2 align="center">Artemis Data Book</H2><h2 align="center">3.3 Financing the Project</H2><h2 align="center">Investment in the Lunar Resources Company</H2><P ALIGN=CENTER><I>Gregory R. Bennett</I></P><P><HR><P><P>Anyone interested in investing in <a href="http://www.tlrc.com/">TheLunar Resources Comapny</a> should also be aware that the first offering isonly the first of several.  We anticipate a series of public offerings,each timed to provide the capital required for each stage of the operation,and your ownership per share will be diluted with each subsequentoffering.</P><P>In the cash-flow analysis of the <a href="/srtemis.html">ArtemisProject</a>, most of the time is spent in the black. That would work fineif we were content to exploit the project's entertainment value at somepoint and fold; however, to realize the Big Bucks profits, we have toaccomplish our goal of establishing a permanent lunar base.  From abusiness standpoint, we're selling a promise, and we have to continue towork toward fulfilling that promise or all we have to sell is just anotherspace fantasy.</P><P>Get the picture?  This thing is set up to drive the Board of Directorstoward the goal of establishing a thriving lunar base, because only bydoing that will they be able to serve the best financial interests of thestockholders.  This is how the power of private enterprise will get us intospace.</P><P>We need to assure that the interests of the initial stockholders areprotected and that folks are rewarded for investing early.  To do this, wedo not intend to have subsequent offerings until we can make the nextoffering at a higher price against reasonably anticipated revenues.  Afterthe initial offering, this becomes a balancing skill -- the anticipatedannualized return from purchasing a share of stock will decline over time,but if we program it right even the last public offering will have anattractive predicted return on investment.</P><P>Let me emphasize "predicted" return on investment.  Obviously we can'tpromise anything; we are venturing into uncharted territory both in spaceand in business.  Nobody has ever tried a private manned space venturebefore, and nobody has ever tried to marry space travel with show business.(Unless you count science fiction, which the Artemis Project isn't.)</P><!-- Nav Bar --><hr size="5"><table align=center border=4 cellpadding = 3 cellspacing=2><tr><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/index.html">ArtemisProject</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/asi_index.html">ArtemisSociety</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/adb/index.html">ArtemisData Book</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="/adb/j/index.html">FAQ</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="/adb/04/index.html">Reference Mission</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.tlrc.com/catalog.html">Catalog</a></b></tr></table><hr size="5"><font size=1>Copyright &#169; 1996 Artemis Society International.Updated Sat, Apr 15, 1996<br>Content by <a href="/bios/bennett.gregory.html">Gregory R. Bennett</a> <ahref="mailto:grb@asi.org">&lt;grb@asi.org&gt;</a>, maintained by <AHREF="MAILTO:simon@eagle.ca">&lt;simon@eagle.ca&gt;</A>.<br>"<a href="/Artemis.html">The Artemis Project</a>"is a trademark of <aHREF="http://www.tlrc.com/Lrc.html">The Lunar ResourcesCompany</a>.</font></body></html>
