<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>3.3 Shipping Cost Analysis</TITLE></HEAD><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><!-- Artemis Data Book --><!-- ADB section 3.3 Financing the Project --><!-- file: /adb/03/03/shipping-cost-analysis.html --><!-- v 1.0 --><h2 align="center">Artemis Data Book</H2><h2 align="center">3.3 Financing the Project</H2><h2 align="center">Shipping Cost Analysis</H2><P ALIGN=CENTER><I>Gregory R. Bennett, Kevin O'Donnell, Jr.</I></P><P><HR><P><P>This is an analysis of how sundry mail-order companies calculate theshipping costs they ask you to add to your order.  This table lists 5 ofthe 12 companies we included in the analysis. </P><P>To make sure we don't offend the companies used as examples, their nameshave been replaced with letters.  Everyone uses different breakpoints, sowe standardized on $10 increments.  You can see in the table where theshipping costs jump.</P><BLOCKQUOTE><PRE>  Mechandise          Shipping and Handling Costs Added       Total      A         B         C        D        E      ------    -----     -----     -----    -----    -----        0.00     2.99      4.95      3.55     4.50     3.95       10.01     3.99      4.95      4.85     4.50     4.95       20.01     4.99      5.95      5.95     5.50     4.95       30.01     5.99      7.45      6.95     6.50     5.95       40.01     6.99      7.45      6.95     7.50     6.95       50.01     7.99      8.85      8.85     8.50     7.95       60.01     7.99      8.85      8.95     8.50     7.95       70.01     7.99      8.85      8.95     9.50     7.95       80.01     7.99     10.35      9.95     9.50     8.95       90.01     7.99     10.35     10.95     9.50     8.95      100.01     7.99     12.00     10.95     9.50     8.95      110.01     7.99     12.00     10.95     9.50     8.95      120.01     7.99     12.00     10.95     9.50     8.95      130.01     7.99     12.00     10.95     9.50     9.95      140.01     7.99     12.00     10.95     9.50     9.95      150.01     7.99     13.50     10.95     9.50     9.95      160.01     7.99     13.50     10.95     9.50     9.95      170.01     7.99     13.50     10.95     9.50     9.95      180.01     7.99     13.50     10.95     9.50     9.95      190.01     7.99     13.50     10.95     9.50     9.95      200.01     7.99     14.95     10.95     9.50     9.95</PRE></BLOCKQUOTE><P>(Shipping costs are constant, or a constant percentage, above $200.)</P><ol type=A><li>general mail order; homey, folksy image; mostly small items<li>Entertainment giant, wide variety of trademark merchandise<li>mail-order calalog, up-scale tech toys<li>mail-order catalog, home improvement stuff<li>high-priced specialty food stores, most business is through mail-ordercatalog stressing Christmas gifts</ol><P>Until now, we calculated the shipping cost for each item based on itsactual cost of packaging and shipping.  People complained about the highshipping charges.  Never mind that those are the real and accurate costs ofgetting an item into the mail; what matters is how people perceive thesituation.</P><P>After studying all those catalogs, it was obvious that successfulmail-order companies base their shipping costs on the total of merchandiseordered.  We took that as empirical evidence that it works (all those folkshave been in business for a long time) and decided to do the same thingwith our shipping costs.</P><P>We ran many sample cases based on the small selection of merchandise wehave in our current catalog.  Suppose someone ordered just one coffee cupor T-shirt; suppose someone ordered a dozen:  how much would we lose onshipping costs?  How much would we be over-charging for shipping?  Why dothe big guys set up their shipping-cost tables the way they do?</P><P>We learned a few really important lessons from this analysis:</P><ol><P><LI>The bigger the company, the more they discourage small orders.</P><P>Look at Company B, the entertainment giant.  They've been marketingtrademark toys since before we were born.  If you order less than $10 ofmerchandise from them, they'll hit you for an additional 50% to send thatone item to you.  (They don't really have many items priced less than $10anyway.)</P><P><LI>The larger the order, the more willing they are to absorb some ofthe shipping cost in reduced profit.</P><P>That makes sense.  If you order one coffee cup, we can't afford toabsorb any of the cost.  But if you order $100 worth of stuff, we can lose$2 in shipping costs without worrying about it.</P><P><LI>Breakpoints in the shipping costs tables are set up to encourage youto add that one more small item to a larger order.</P><P>This shows up in our table a little bit.  If you want a T-shirt (pricedat $12.50), it won't cost you additional shipping to put one of thosemagnet-backed "Artemis" buttons ($1.25) on your refrigerator.  But if allyou want is one of those magnets and that's all you order, the time ittakes for a clerk to fill your order will eat you alive.</P><P><LI>Companies typically have 6 or 7 breakpoints in the shipping-costtable.  We followed the same rule.  It makes for a tidy littletable.</P></ol><P><HR><P><H3>The Lunar Resources Company Catalog</H3><P><h4>Prices and Ordering Information</h4></P><BLOCKQUOTE><table cellpadding = 1 cellspacing=1><tr><thalign=center>Merchandise<th align=center>Price<thalign=center>Notes<br></tr><tr><td><AHREF="http://www.tlrc.com/Analog9501.html">January 1995 Analog</a> <tdalign=right>$ 3.95<br></tr><tr><td><AHREF="http://www.tlrc.com/Poster.html">Artemis Project OverviewPoster</a><td align=right>$ 2.50<br></tr><tr><td><AHREF="http://www.tlrc.com/moonbase.logo.html">Moonbase Artemis Mug </a><tdalign=right>$ 7.50<br></tr><tr><td><AHREF="http://www.tlrc.com/buttondesc.html">Refrigerator Magnet</a><td align=right>$ 1.25<br></tr><tr><td><AHREF="http://www.tlrc.com/buttondesc.html">Artemis Button</A><tdalign=right>$ 1.00<br></tr><tr><td><AHREF="http://ww