<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>3.4 Calender Production Notes</TITLE></HEAD><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><!-- Artemis Data Book --><!-- ADB section 3.4 Revenue Sources --><!-- file: /adb/03/04/calender-notes.html --><!-- Keywords: marketing electronic calender internet pictures art  --><!-- v 1.0 --><h2 align="center">Artemis Data Book</H2><h2 align="center">3.4 Revenue Sources</H2><h2 align="center">Calender Production Notes</H2><P ALIGN=CENTER><I>Gregory R. Bennett</I></P><P><HR><P><P>The only drawback to a weekly calendar right now is that we don'thave 52 gosh-wow illustrations to put on it.  It sounds easy at first, butselecting each photo or illustration takes time, and of course creating themfrom scratch takes lots of time.</P><P>A calendar on the World Wide Web is a nifty idea.  In fact, we'veexperimented with programming up a routine, in Hypercard, that generates anhtmlscript for a monthly calendar.  We don't have much to list in the dates yet,but we could at least have links to issues of the Angus Bay Morning News(assuming we can get ABMN going sometime soon).</P><P>For electronic calendars, or variations on paper ones, we're back tocalling for volunteers.  I won't be able to put much time into it for the nextfew weeks, and the next few weeks are when it would have to be done.</P><P>Printing up a collection of 11x17 illustrations is a good idea.  That<a href="/adb/04/">reference mission</a> <ahref="http://www.tlrc.com/catalog.html">poster</A> is neat, but it'sfrustrating -- it costs more for a mailing tube than to print the thing, soyou wind up having to pay as much forit as you would for a full-color, full-size poster in a local store.  If wecan get a collection of illustrations together, then we'd be able to send alot more cool stuff for little additional cost.</P><P>See also <a href="/adb/03/04/calenders.html">related document</a> onsteps involved in making a saleable calender.</A><!-- Nav Bar --><hr size="5"><table align=center border=4 cellpadding = 3 cellspacing=2><tr><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/index.html">ArtemisProject</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/asi_index.html">ArtemisSociety</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/adb/index.html">ArtemisData Book</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="/adb/j/index.html">FAQ</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="/adb/04/index.html">Reference Mission</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.tlrc.com/catalog.html">Catalog</a></b></tr></table><hr size="5"><font size=1>Copyright &#169; 1996 Artemis Society International.Updated Sun, Apr 21, 1996<br>Content by <a href="/bios/bennett.gregory.html">Gregory R. Bennett</a> <ahref="mailto:grb@asi.org">&lt;grb@asi.org&gt;</a>, maintained by <AHREF="MAILTO:simon@eagle.ca">&lt;simon@eagle.ca&gt;</A>.<br>"<a href="/Artemis.html">The Artemis Project</a>"is a trademark of <aHREF="http://www.tlrc.com/Lrc.html">The Lunar ResourcesCompany</a>.</font></body></html>
