<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>3.7 Labor Pool Proposal</TITLE></HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<!-- Artemis Data Book -->
<!-- ADB section 3.7 Work Breakdown Structure -->
<!-- file: /adb/03/07/labor-pool-concept.html -->
<!-- v 1.0 -->
<h2 align="center">Artemis Data Book</H2>
<h2 align="center">3.7 Work Breakdown Structure</H2>
<h2 align="center">Labor Pool Proposal</H2>
<P ALIGN=CENTER><I>R. Alonzo Fyfe</I></P>
<P><HR><P>

<P>I would like to propose that a "call for resumes" be sent out
for those who wish to volunteer their technical knowledge and expertise to
the Artemis Project. These resumes are to be stored in a file which Task
Force leaders can access in order to evaluate and to pick personnel whose
knowledge and expertise can be used to complete the tasks assigned to
them.</P>

<P>Before a call for resumes can be made, it is important to have the
necessary infrastructure established in order to efficiently process these
resumes. But because this infrastructure is needed to handle the task,
determining the nature of this infrastructure is dependent on (and best
discussed after) the identification of the task it is to be designed to
accomplish.</P>

<P>Once the infrastructure for managing the input from a call for resumes
is set up, a message is sent out on the mailing list, perhaps to the
newsgroup sci.space.policy and attached to the web page, asking those
interested in volunteering time and talents to the Artemis Project to
submit resumes that identify their fields of interests and the talents,
expertise, and other resources that they can contribute to fulfilling the
Artemis Project's goals.</P>

<P>The type of message I am thinking of would look something like this:</P>

<BLOCKQUOTE><P>The Artemis organization is entering a new phase. We have
sat for a while discussing what we are going to do. We have even sketched 
out a few ideas on electronic napkins and pieces of scrap paper scattered 
around the dining room table. We are now ready to roll up our sleeves and 
head on out to the shop to start converting ideas into something real.</P>

<P>"Many people have volunteered to contribute their expertise, the benefits
of their experience, and their time to this project. We would like, at
this time, to take stock of the resources that you have offered. We would
like to ask those of you interested in contributing to the project to
submit two documents:</P>

<ol type="1">
<P><LI>A short resume (1,000 word limit) listing:
<ol type=A>
<li>The type of work you are interested in doing.
<li>The amount of time that you are willing to contribute. A listing of
specific hours that you are willing to work, if possible, will be a plus.
<li>Your recent employment history.
<li>Your educational history
<li>Relevant honors and professional associations
<li>Recent relevant work experience and/or educational training. This
should highlight specific projects that you have been involved in and/or
classes you have taken that you think make you uniquely qualified to
perform the tasks you are asking to perform.</ol>

<P><lI>An even shorter (150 word limit) cameo - a short paragraph
highlighting the key points that can be found in your resume.</P></ol>

<P>We want to stress that we are NOT yet asking for applications for
employment. We are not yet at a stage where we can start offering people
jobs. But we have heard from quite a few people who share our enthusiasm
and interest in adventuring into this final frontier and who, like us, are
eager to get to work now. Some of us are already getting our hands dirty.
We are eager to do as much as possible as quickly as possible, so we want
to know exactly what resources, in terms of time, talent, and training, we
can draw upon.</P>

<P> Naturally, when we do get to the stage where start hiring people, we will
look first at those who helped us the most in getting to that stage.</p>

<P> We seek to make these cameos and resumes available to our task leaders.
The cameos should contain a list of key words, so that when a task force
leader needs somebody with particular skills he can search the directory 
for the relevant key words and get a list of those with the relevant 
expertise. The cameos will allow the task leader to narrow his search. 
They can then call up the most promising resumes and contact the
volunteers.</P>

<P>Please be assured that the resumes and cameos will be kept confidential;
access to this information will be limited to Artemis executives and
authorized task leaders</P>

<P>Also, please note that we are seeking not only engineers and scientists.
We have a ton of administrative work that needs to be done, from answering
mail, database maintenance, electronic filing, and web page maintenance, to
accounting and legal work. There is room in Artemis for everyone.</P>

<P>If you are among those of us too anxious to see the final frontier opened
up to wait, please send your resumes and cameos to
Volunteer@.............</P></BLOCKQUOTE>


<H4>Resources needed:</H4>

<P>For the sake of efficiency, I suggest that a separate e-mail address be
set up for receiving resumes. Furthermore, I recommend the name 
"volunteer" in this address or something similar as a means of reinforcing
the fact that those who send in resumes are not applying for employment.</P>

<P>Computer directory space needs to be set aside for these directories
(with appropriate backup - the time and talents people will be offering
are too valuable to risk losing to a computer crash).</p>

<P>A team should be established to manage these resumes. This department 
should be staffed in advance with enough people to receive the resumes and to
place them in the appropriate directory. Also, they should acknowledge the
receipt of all resumes and cameos, and request clarification (or reject)
those that are too long, missing a list of key words, indicate that the
volunteer is mentally unstable, and the like.</P>

<P>Also, this Department of Personnel will be responsible for handling the
search requests submitted by task force leaders and in transmitting the
results of the search, and in transmitting resumes to those requesting
them, and maintaining the security of this database. The department will
need to keep this resume file updated by noting such things as: who is
already working on a task, removing applicants who no longer want to
volunteer their time or who want to take a leave of absence, and making
changes in such things as level of training, professional experience,
e-mail address, and areas of interest.</p>

<P>Task force managers should be required to fill out a performance
evaluation on each member of their task force at regular periods (six
months, recommended) which are also to be attached to volunteer's file.
However, these files should be secured, and only the department
administrator should have access to them.</P>


<H4>Example:</H4>

<P>For the work that I have been assigned, I would like to have the input of
individuals who have experience in sales and marketing. I would send an
e-mail to whomever maintains the labor pool with this request. They would
run the name through the system and generate a short list of people with
those skills and mail me the cameos of those people. I would read through
those and pick 4 or 5 resumes I would like to look at. Once I get the
resumes, I can then make my choice and e-mail those who seem the best
qualified.</P>



<!-- Nav Bar -->
