<HTML> <HEAD> <TITLE>Why Someone Would Oppose the ArtemisProject</TITLE> </HEAD><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><!-- Artemis Data Book section 3.8 Other Business Issues --><!-- file: /adb/03/08/causes-of-opposition.html --><!-- Keywords: opposition roadblocks commercial competition government  --><h2 align="center">Artemis Data Book</H2><h2 align="center">3.8 Other Business Issues</H2><h2 align="center">Why Someone Would Oppose the Artemis Project</H2><P><HR><P><!-- I'm stuck. Where should we stick this? Surely not in Project Overview,but then it's got nothing to do with ASI. --><P>We have looked at those who were opposed to the project, and analyzedwhether they might have ulterior motives.  In fact, we've expended aconsiderable amount of manpower on that issue.  Here's where we think weare in defining the reasons people don't want this to happen.</P><H3>Ego</H3><P>Within the space-fan community, it's mostly ego more than anything else."Not invented here" is a major driver.  The most vocal opponents areiconoclasts who enjoy boasting about their own abilities while attackingothers.  The net has its fare share of people like that.  Some folks just liketo show everybody how smart they are, and the easiest way to do that is totake an adversarial position.</P><H3>Business Competition</H3><P>A few people perceive the <a href="/artemis.html">Artemis Project</a> ascompetition for their own lunar projects.  That worries us because it meanswe're not getting the point across that we're doing our best to provide amechanism to create demand for those projects.</P><P>Frankly, we made a mistake in starting out with a commercial companybefore we put the <a href="/asi_index.html">Artemis Society</a> together,and now we're working hard to correct that.  For this thing to work, wehave to make it attractive to many companies all over the world -- it notonly has to make good business sense, but has to be palatable in terms ofbusiness ego, too.  People justifiably have great pride in the work they'vedone to build a business, and however we tailor the <ahref="/artemis.html">Artemis Project</a> it has to let each company retainits own individual identity.</P><P>Right now it's a question of which business leaders have the guts tostep up and support the project, putting their corporate reputation on theline <I>before</I> "the Artemis Project" becomes a household word.</P><H3>Prefer Government Programs</H3><P>A few people (maybe two or three) have intensely disliked the ideabecause it would weaken their efforts to get the U.S. government to do amanned lunar base.  We can sympathize with those feelings, but after poundingon the government for the past 20 years to return to moon, we're convinced thatit's just not going to happen.  And if the U.S. government did do a lunarbase, it would really be a setback for opening the space frontier; a governmentfacility would be just that, not a program to get folks like us to the moon.</P><P>A couple of the vocal opponents do have a vested financial interest inthe government having a monopoly on manned space flight -- when your day jobdepends on advising the government, it's not fun to watch NASA's budgetdwindling while a bunch of upstarts start talking about commercial aerospace.(Admittedly, at the core of those upstarts are veterans of the U.S. spaceprograms; but we're upstarts in the commercial world.)<P>We're happy to report, however, that <I>none</I> of those vocalopponents has a NASA civil service badge; NASA went on record in favor ofthis thing as soonas they heard about it (there has not, however, been a policy statementmade).  And we have spoken to the most experienced NASA aerospacecontractors, who are all for it, too.</P><H3>Fear</H3><P>Among the general population we've told about the <ahref="/artemis.html">Artemis Project</a>,though, you'll find a reaction you might not expect: fear.  Fear of gettingtheir hopes up.  Fear of being told they can go, too; and then finding outit's not going to happen (again).  Fear of failure.  Fear of success.  It's areal human emotion, and one we have to deal with.</P><H3>Concept Shock</H3><P>The whole idea is so big and so complex that it defies the ability ofthe human mind to encompass the whole program in a single thought.  And it'sso different from their experience, many people who are currently working inthe U.S. government's space programs just can't believe it.</P><P>Here's an example of concept shock at work: Some of the team who did theengineering integration work for SpaceLab -- the European Space Agency's<a href="/adb/04/01/01/01/01/shuttle.html">Shuttle</a>-based laboratory --couldn't believe that <a href="/adb/04/03/06/01/">SPACEHAB</a> couldpossibly be done for the amount of money they had budgeted.  Keep in mindthat SpaceLab and SPACEHAB were done by the same company in the same city.But when the SpaceLab engineers transferred to the SPACEHAB program, theylearned that indeed a commercially developed manned laboratory could bebuilt for much less than 10% of the cost of a government laboratory,matching function for function, specification for specification.</P><P>The point here is that people whose entire career is in governmentaerospace have a terrible time understanding commercial aerospace.  Those ofus who started in commercial and then moved to government projects after afew years have had a similar hard time adjusting -- sometimes it is a matterofdeveloping a whole new level of stoicism.  It's just plain the nature ofgovernment programs, and has been since the days of ancient Rome.</P><H3>Legitimate Concerns</H3><P>Now, all that said, many people have raised very legitimate issues.This is a great goodness -- it forces us to be more rigorous in our researchand analysis. When this happens, we devote manpower and fix it.</P><P>We'll admit we've grown weary of answering the same <ahref="FRO.html">issues</a> we've addressed many times before; but we knewthat would be a factor from the first day. There's value even to thatweariness, though: it drives us to write it down and continuously improvethe way we relate the answers until we have a succinct, understandablestory for every one of those concerns.</P><!-- Nav Bar --><hr size="5"><table align=center border=4 cellpadding = 3 cellspacing=2><tr><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/index.html">ArtemisProject</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/asi_index.html">ArtemisSociety</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/adb/index.html">ArtemisData Book</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="/adb/j/index.html">FAQ</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="/adb/04/index.html">Reference Mission</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.tlrc.com/catalog.html">Catalog</a></b></tr></table><hr size="5"><font size=-2>Copyright &#169; 1996 Artemis Society International.Updated Fri, March 15, 1996<br>Content by <a href="/bios/bennett.gregory.html">Gregory R. Bennett</a> <ahref="mailto:grb@asi.org">&lt;grb@asi.org&gt;</a>, maintained by <AHREF="MAILTO:simon@eagle.ca">&lt;simon@eagle.ca&gt;</A>.<br><a href="http://www.asi.org/index.html">The Artemis Project</a>is a trademark of <aHREF="http://www.tlrc.com/Lrc.html">The Lunar Resources Company</a>.</font></body></html>
