<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>5. Lunar Solar Sail Race Notes</TITLE></HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<!-- Artemis Data Book -->
<!-- ADB section 5. Mission Options -->
<!-- file: /adb/05/lunar-solar-sail-race.html -->
<!-- Keywords: habitat robot Carnegie-Mellon University Lunacorp regolith
heat insulation bury -->
<!-- v 1.0 -->
<h2 align="center">Artemis Data Book</H2>
<h2 align="center">5. Mission Options</H2>
<h2 align="center">Lunar Solar Sail Race Notes</H2>
<P ALIGN=CENTER><I>Gregory R. Bennett</I></P>
<P><HR><P>

<P>In a brainstorming session among some Artemis Society members, the idea
to have a solar sail race around the moon came up. Unfortunately, the third
party which pursued the idea was unable to secure corporate sponsorhip.
Part of the problem was the nature of the program -- a solar sail race
would be a slow-motion event as seen on television -- but it seems the
major problem was that they didn't find the Right Person to handle
marketing the program.</P>

<P>There's a paperback book out chock full of nifty solar sail stories,
with a blurb in the back about the proposed project. It is entitled
<I>Project Solar Sail</i>.</P>

<P>Perhaps because of the lack of interest from corporate sponsors, they
are really big on the idea of getting government funding for this.
However, it may be a good idea to look again at private enterprise,
specifically professional sports and events like the America's Cup sailboat
race, to determine why these things have such widespread appeal.  The
answer is:</P>

<oL>
<LI>Home Team as a substitute for war heroes in human psychology
<LI>Stories (games) based on familiar characters and setting
<LI>Ability for sports fan to be an expert on the subject
<LI>Familiarity with the setting because most of these sports are things
anyone can do, on a personal scale
<LI>Wagering</OL>

<P>From an economic standpoint, wagering is probably the strongest
appeal. However, a successful solar sail race would need to address all
these elements. On the last round, the presentation of the race was too
impersonal. To sell entertainment, ya gotta have people in the picture.</P>

<P>Building a spacecraft for a race like this is not a killer effort.
Almost any college engineering department could handle it, with the
students providing the slave labor and the profs providing the technical
guidance. Obviously ASI has the expertise needed to design such a
spacecraft, though we're currently too spread out to build it. Ditto for
the National Space Society.</P>

<P>How to do this, one step at a time:</P>

<ul type=circle>
<LI>Get the teams signed up, assuming the funding will come
<LI>Get an expert on the gambling industry to handle the gambling
concessions all over the world; wherever it's legal
<LI>Develop a plan for television specials and news coverage; emphasize the
people on the teams, not the spacecraft
<LI>Build a detailed business plan with all those elements
<LI>Get commitment for launch services, assuming funding available
<LI>If the business plan is financially viable, go out for investors
<LI>Then, and only then, press the START button on the program
</UL>

<P>The key is finding someone to organize and lead the effort. The
leader would need skills in management and marketing; and it would be much
better if he were <I>not</I> a rocket scientist. Technically-oriented managers
tend to concentrate too much on the hardware instead of the people who make it
happen.</P>


<!-- Nav Bar -->
