<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>5.4.1 Near-Earth Asteroid Mining Study</TITLE></HEAD><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><!-- Artemis Data Book --><!-- ADB section 5.4.1 Near-Earth Asteroid --><!-- file: /adb/05/04/01/css-asteroid-mining-study.html --><!-- Keywords: asteroid mining elecrtostatic propulsion space developmentcommercial manned space investment --><!-- v 1.0 --><h2 align="center">Artemis Data Book</H2><h2 align="center">5.4.1 Near-Earth Asteroid</H2><h2 align="center">Near-Earth Asteroid Mining Study</H2><P><HR><P><P>Here is an article I wrote over a year ago about asteroid capture. I cansee now that there are some errors in some assumptions, but the flavor ofit is still nice.</P><P>This is obviously adaptable to Artemis Project infrastructure, and couldbe much cheaper if leveraged with <ahref="/adb/04/03/10/04/oxygen-extraction.html">lunar oxygen</a> and usedexisting spacecraft.</P><P>With revenues from the first few missions to fund a project similar tothis, it is a possible example of reinvesting revenues in space.</P><P><HR><P><P>A BEGINNING FOR SPACE RESOURCES DEVELOPMENT<BR>By Gregory Nemitz</P><P>Here is a possible mission that investment capital might be found for. Themission is to capture an Earth-crossing asteroid and bring it into lunarorbit or to the L-5 between the Earth & Moon.  A prime objective of thismission is to establish a precedent for property rights to resources inspace.</P><P>The capture of an asteroid would put megatons of mass in a situationwhere it would be relatively easy for industry to make a profit.</P><P>It is a three-phase mission.  The first is an initial survey mission onan Earth-crossing asteroid with a 2-4 year period.  The second phase wouldestablish a "beachhead" volatile gas collection facility.  The third phasewould  install the propulsion system and begin trajectory diversion tolunar orbit, or the L-5.</P><P>The initial survey mission can be done today with existing Russianflight hardware.  Two launches, a Soyuz and a Proton KM cargo transport,can be bought for around $60 million. The two-person crew will have as longas two weeks to explore and sample the asteroid.</P><P>To pay for the estimated $70 million cost for the survey mission'scompletion, we would approach those  who would  invest in the corporation,planning to realize a profit on the survey mission alone. The cable TVnetworks, the movie industry, the advertising industry, the miningindustry, aerospace companies, and others, are possibilites.</P><P>One of the survey mission goals is to lay claim and establish ownership rights ofthe asteroid's resources. The corporation would be the owner. This issuemust be resolved in the World Court.  For space development to take place,property rights must be secure. This test case can open the doors to therapid development of resources in space and define, by example, howenterprises may fairly hold just claims.</P><P>The second phase occurs when the asteroid returns to the Earth'svicinity 2-4 years later. A maximum stay time at the asteroid is desired,maybe 3-4 weeks. The crew will install a gas collection facility, customdesigned from the information learned in the survey mission. A powersupply, vacuum pumps, a gas liquefaction and separation plant, and storagetankage (empty booster casings?) are installed. The entire asteroid isenveloped in a plastic bag, and 1/4 psi of CO<FONT SIZE=1>2</FONT> is usedto inflate and pressurize the bag.  The CO<FONT SIZE=1>2</FONT> causes amini-greenhouse effect to warm the asteroid as it journeys sunward, andcauses the release of frozen gasses.  These gasses are automaticallypumped, liquefied, separated, and stored for use during the thirdphase.</P><P>Again, Russian flight hardware may be the most economical choice, butmaybe by then, (1998?) the Delta Clipper, SSTO will be on-line.</P><P>A prime mission of the second phase is to reinforce the claim made 2-4years previously by tangibly improving the property.  By this time thelegal world will have to come to a consensus in regard to property rightsin space.  Nothing will be resolved until some enterprise makes a claim.The law deals in realities, not conjecture. If we present the world a FaitAccompli, the issue will be resolved.</P><P>The third phase is the actual recovery of the asteroid.  We launch aself-contained habitat for 6-8 men and women, a supply shed, an equipmentgarage, and a three or four Topaz fission reactors, to rendezvous with thereturning asteroid.  The crew will have a 2-4 year mission.</P><P>A possible use for the stored gasses collected by the second phase isreaction mass for a nuclear Nerva engine.  For the event of a emergencyreturn flight to Earth,  when the third phase crew is riding the asteroidfor 2-4 years.</P><P>The asteroid trajectory diversion would be done with electrostatic dustaccelerators.  The asteroid's material is mined and then pulverized in arock-crushing mill to face powder fineness.  Any valuable elements(determined by the initial survey mission) are refined out. The waste dustis given a strong electrostatic charge. The dust is then accelerated down atube and away as fast as possible, for reaction mass.  The dust is fineenough for the solar wind to blow it out of the solar system, reducing thepollution problem inherent in pellet guns, as O'Neil proposed.  Electricityis provided by the 3 or 4 Russian Topaz nuclear reactors.</P><P>The crew takes along 6 dust engines, mounting trusses, appropriate toolsand machines to do the work of installing the engines, and mining andrefining the dust efficiently.  The excavation for the dust would be thetunnels and galleries for leased habitation, when the rock arrives at theL-5.</P><P>A simplified timeline shows the sequence:</P><PRE> Mar 1993 -  Jul 1993                   Jul 1993 - Dec 1993 Proposal developed                     Initial funding sought G.Nemitz & SD L-5                      $100k for salaries & expns. 1994                                   1995 Commitments for $70M                   Initial survey mission acquired, Asteroid identified          succeeds. Samples Russian hardware booked                returned are studied. 1995-1996                              1996 Second round funding                   Gas collection facility sought.  $500M?                        designed. 1997                                   1998 GCF built.  Flight hardware            Asteroid returns (~3yr pd) booked.                                Second mission succeeds. 1998-1999                              1999 -2000 Third round funding                    Engines, habitat, mining gear sought.  $2B?  Dust                    built.  Flight hardware booked. engines designed. 2001                                   2001-2004 Asteroid returns (~3yr pd)             Third mission installs engines, Third mission arrives at rock,         diverts asteroid's course. Crew takes up residence.               Crew mines ores, refines bullion,                                        digs Habitation areas. 2004                                   2005 Asteroid delivered to                  Bullion delivered to investors Lunar orbit; or L-5                    Lots leased on new real estate 1993-2005: A twelve year project.</PRE><!-- Nav Bar --><hr size="5"><table align=center border=4 cellpadding = 3 cellspacing=2><tr><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/index.html">ArtemisProject</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/asi_index.html">ArtemisSociety</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/adb/index.html">ArtemisData Book</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="/adb/j/index.html">FAQ</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="/adb/04/index.html">Reference Mission</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.tlrc.com/catalog.html">Catalog</a></b></tr></table><hr size="5"><font size=-2>Copyright &#