<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>5.4.1 Near-Earth Asteroid Mining Article</TITLE></HEAD><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><!-- Artemis Data Book --><!-- ADB section 5.4.1 Near-Earth Asteroid --><!-- file: /adb/05/04/01/economist-mine-nea-study.html --><!-- Keywords: asteroid mining elecrtostatic propulsion space developmentcommercial manned space investment --><!-- v 1.0 --><h2 align="center">Artemis Data Book</H2><h2 align="center">5.4.1 Near-Earth Asteroid</H2><h2 align="center">Near-Earth Asteroid Mining Article</H2><P><HR><P><P>A December 1994 issue of "The Economist" from London has, of all things,a four column article on asteroid mining.  The article goes into detailsproposed by Dr. Jeffery Kargel of the US Geological Survey's branch ofastrogeology in Flagstaff, Arizona.</p><P>Kargel's recently published analysis in the "Journal of GeophysicalResearch", focuses on the platinum group metals found in asteroids.These metals are platinum, iridium, osmium, palladium, rhenium, andrubidium.  Dr. Kargel calculates a one kilometer diameter, platinum-rich metallic asteroid, contains 400,000 tons of precious metals.  At the1990 prices he estimated, that's $5 trillion-worth.</P><P>If that 1 km asteroid was mined and the metals brought to Earth, overa 20 year period, the world's supply of those metals would increaseten-fold.  The production/price relationship would cause a drasticslump in the price of those metals.  An example would be the 87,000tons of rubidium in the asteroid, worth $171 billion today, would fall to$5 billion.</P><P>Even after the price crash, the asteroid would be worth $323 billion.to recover these resources there are four identified problems: gettingto the asteroid, processing the ore, refining the ore, and bringing ithome to Earth.</P><P>The article characterizes getting there to be relatively easy, as it canbe easier to get to an Earth crossing asteroid than it is to go to themoon.  To return the metal the article suggests an electro-magneticcatapult to fling super-ingots (20 tons) at the Earth. (Yikes!!)  It doesmention that there could be political problems associated with thatplan.  To transport 400,000 tons over 20 years would mean launchingthree 20 ton projectiles every day.  It mentions that the energyimparted for delivery could be as little as a kw-h per kg of metaldelivered.</P><P>As to processing, it suggests either warming or cooling the asteroid.Warming it to molten allows working with handy-sized blobs of metal,or one could place the solar power collector between the sun and theasteroid and allow it to cool so that it becomes brittle and be moreeasily shattered into workable pieces.</P><P>The article says that the process could be mostly automated, but that"humans are good fixers and improvisers, and may be worth theirweight in rocket fuel."  Refining the metal is seen as a trivial problemthat process engineers can readily solve.</P><P>Given the current estimates of near-earth asteroids, about 60 of themare likely to be both metal and 1 km across.  The platinum content willvary but about one in ten should be at least as rich as the hypotheticalasteroid Dr. Kargel examples.</P><P>The article closes by suggesting that there may never be a companywith sufficient resources and tolerance for risk to mine an asteroidpurely on commercial grounds.  It then suggests that an Earth-colliding asteroid might be diverted by mining the metal and flinging itaway to divert the asteroid's catastrophic course, thus making a buckand saving the world.</P><!-- Nav Bar --><hr size="5"><table align=center border=4 cellpadding = 3 cellspacing=2><tr><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/index.html">ArtemisProject</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/asi_index.html">ArtemisSociety</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/adb/index.html">ArtemisData Book</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="/adb/j/index.html">FAQ</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="/adb/04/index.html">Reference Mission</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.tlrc.com/catalog.html">Catalog</a></b></tr></table><hr size="5"><font size=-2>Copyright &#169; 1996 Artemis Society International.Updated Mon, Apr 1, 1996<br>Content by Gregory Nemitz<a href="mailto:G.NEMITZ@genie.com">&lt;g.nemitz@genie.com&gt;</a>,maintained by<A HREF="MAILTO:simon@eagle.ca">&lt;simon@eagle.ca&gt;</A>.<br>"<a href="/Artemis.html">The Artemis Project</a>"is a trademark of <aHREF="http://www.tlrc.com/Lrc.html">The Lunar Resources Company</a>.</font></body></html>
