<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>5.5.2 Benefits for Manned Landing from Sample
Return</TITLE></HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<!-- Artemis Data Book -->
<!-- ADB section 5.5.2 Contribution to Long-Range Plan -->
<!-- file: /adb/05/05/02/reduce-manned-flight-cost.html -->
<!-- Keywords: telerobot cost revenue artemis project gains transferred
lunar sample return business plan -->
<!-- v 1.0 -->
<h2 align="center">Artemis Data Book</H2>
<h2 align="center">5.5.2 Contribution to Long-Range Plan</H2>
<h2 align="center">Benefits for Manned Landing from Sample Return</H2>
<P ALIGN=CENTER><I>Simon Rowland, R. Alonzo Fyfe</I></P>
<P><HR><P>


<P>One must not neglect to include the substantial benefits to the <a
href="/artemis.html">Artemis Project</a> in infrastructure, marketing,
experience, and credibility arising from a commercial sample return
mission.</P>

<BLOCKQUOTE><table cellpadding=2>
<th><td> </td><td> <B>Total <br> costs</B> </td><td> <B>Initial <br>
costs</B> </td><td> <B>Recurring <br> costs</B> </td><td> <B>Value for <br>
Manned Mission</B> </td></th>
<tr><td> Launcher </td><td> $110 M </td><td> $0 </td><td> $110 M </td><td>
$5 M </td><td> <a href="#1">[1]</a> </td></tr>
<tr><td> Carrier Spacecraft </td><td> $50 M </td><td> $30 M </td><td> $20 M
</td><td> $7 M </td><td> <a href="#2">[2]</a> </td></tr>
<tr><td> Robotic Element </td><td> $70 M </td><td> $50 M </td><td> $20 M
</td><td> $68 M </td><td> <a href="#3">[3]</a> </td></tr>
<tr><td> Mission Control Element </td><td> $40 M </td><td> $35 M </td><td>
$5 M </td><td> $36 M </td><td> <a href="#4">[4]</a> </td></tr>
<tr><td> Recovery Operations </td><td> $30 M </td><td> $2 M </td><td> $28 M
</td><td> $0 </td><td> <a href="#5">[5]</a> </td></tr>
<tr><td> Marketing </td><td> $50 M </td><td> $40 M </td><td> $10 M
</td><td> $5 M </td><td> <a href="#6">[6]</a> </td></tr>
<tr><td> Program Wraps </td><td> $70 M </td><td> $32 M </td><td> $38 M
</td><td> $0 </td><td> <a href="#7">[7]</a> </td></tr>
<tr> </tr><tr><td> <B>Total</B> </td><td> $420 M </td><td> $189 M </td><td>
$231 M </td><td> <B>$121 M</B> </td></tr></table></BLOCKQUOTE>



<H3><a name="1">1. Launcher</a></H3>

<P>This hardware is not transferable to the Artemis Project, as we will be
renting other peoples' facilities and craft. This will, however, train 20
people, previously worth $50/hour, to be worth the equivalent of a
consultant at $100/hour. For 3 years of employment until the launch of the
manned mission, this amounts to, assuming 20% raise over the period leading
to launch, an increased value of personnel of $4.8 million dollars.</P>

<H3><a name="2">2. Carrier Spacecraft</a></H3>

<P>40% of this category is production cost. As we will farm the spacecraft
construction work out to McDonnell Douglas or some other aerospace company,
there would be no direct benefit to the Artemis Project.</P>

<P>The other 60% of the Carrier Spacecraft category is development. Assume
80% of the cost is skilled labour, the other 20% being workstations,
models, software, etc. If 10% of the engineering work is transferrable to
the manned project, $3 million dollars would be saved.</P>

<P>The rest of the development cost, being computer workstations and
expensive engineering software, is mostly reusable. The models and such
would not be, but at least 70% of the non-labor expenditures should be
reusable. This represents $4.5 million.</P>

<PRE>        Development Labor       $3.0M
        Development Equipment   $7.2M
       --------------------------------
        Total                   $7.2M</PRE>


<H3><a name="3">3. Robotic Element</a></H3>

<P>As the development cost of the robotic element is $50 million, with 70%
of the telerobot development engineering transferable to the nearly
identical <a href="/adb/04/02/05/04/">lunar base telerobots</a>, $35
million worth of work and experience can be reused.</P>

<P>Here, because the tasks are nearly identical, 30% of the non-labor
production costs are reusable. This makes $3 million worth of computers, 
telerobot models, battery mockups, etc. No parts are reused from the 
contractor.</P>

<P>Finally, there is no reason not to land the robots at the site of the <a
href="/adb/04/">manned landing</a>. This would leave two perfectly good
telerobots for use at lunar base, with each having a value of $20 million,
plus launch to the moon valued at about $10 million.</P>

<PRE>        Development Equipment   $3.0M
        Development Engineering $35M
        Reusable Telerobots     $30M
       -------------------------------
        Total                   $68M</PRE>


<H3><a name="4">4. Mission Control Equipment</a></H3>

<P>The ground communications stations, sample processing, and computer
equipment would all be reusable. There is nearly nothing of the one-time
cost which can't be used for the manned flight (save upgrades). Assuming
95% of the equipment can be adapted for the manned flight, $33.3M of
equipment is usable.</P>

<P>The recurring cost is assumed to be manpower to operate the machinery,
and having operated the same machinery under similar conditions is
excellent training for tracking station operators, etc. Assuming it raises
their hourly rate from $40 to $70, and 80% of the recurring cost is labor,
$2.7M of training is received.</P>

<PRE>        Training                $2.7M
        Equipment               $33.3M
       --------------------------------
        Total                   $36.0M</PRE>


<H3><a name="5">5. Recovery</a></H3>

<P>No money is assumed saved from recovery.</P>


<H3><a name="6">6. Marketing</a></H3>

<P>Although the marketing expenditures would probably be specifically for
the Lunar Sample Return project, it is likely that the simple space
awareness and concept-shock reduction will be valuable for any
space-related marketing. This might be valued at 10% the cost of the Lunar
Sample Return marketing budget, or $5 million.</P>

<P>Also, marketing plans can blow up just like rockets can, and do far more
financial damage. The Sample Return Mission will provide valuable
experience that will make later efforts much more popular. This will
directly increase the profitability of the Reference Mission, as with
experience the next marketing campaign wil undoubtedly be more safe,
effective and efficient. What we don't know about this market could cost
us, both in terms of marketing mistakes and missed opportunities.</P>


<H3><a name="7">7. Project Wraps</a></H3>

<P>Since the Project Wraps are mostly labor, no money is assumed saved
from this section.</P>


<h3>Finally...</h3>

<P>The Sample Return Mission will generate a list of contacts that, 
itself, will be of great value. More importantly, efficient business dealings 
depend on accurate information. Many businesses these days are spending a 
great deal of effort learning as much as they can about their customers
(particularly their larger customers) so that they can better meet their
customers' needs (and keep the competition at a distance). The Reference
Mission will obtain benefits both as a customer whose suppliers will have
obtained better information about it, and as a supplier who will learn a
great deal about its customers (video production companies, retail
outlets, etc.). No doubt, some of this education will result in changes
in the Reference Mission, will are likely to increase its profitability.</P>


