</DOCHDR>
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>5.5.3 Moonrock Marketing Strategy</TITLE></HEAD><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><!-- Artemis Data Book --><!-- ADB section 5.5.3 Business Plan, 3.3 Financing the Project --><!-- file: /adb/03/03/moonrock-marketing-strategy.html/adb/05/05/03/moonrock-marketing-strategy.html  --><!-- Keywords: moonrock regolith sales financing funding marketingmerchandising merchandise comapny experience products distribution taskshow you can help --><!-- v 1.0 --><h2 align="center">Artemis Data Book</H2><h2 align="center">5.5.3 Business Plan</H2><h2 align="center">3.3. Financing the Project</H2><h2 align="center">Moonrock Marketing Strategy</H2><I><P ALIGN=CENTER>R. Alonzo Fyfe</P></I><P><HR><P><P>It may be a little early to create a marketing survey for moonrockproducts. What I would like to offer at this point is a potential marketingstrategy and some tasks associated with that strategy.</P><H3>I. Use Established Companies</H3><P>Just as there is good reason to use established aerospace companies forspace hardware, there is good reason to go with professional companieswith respect to marketing the final products.  The idea is to sell lunarmaterial wholesale, in large blocks, to companies who would, then, breakit down and sell it on the market. For example, 500kg of material can besold to a company that supplies research institutes, 150kg to a companythat supplies museums, 500kg can be sold to governments, etc. ASI shouldpurchase (at discount prices) a block from LRC and contract with companiesthat specialize in collectables for creating Artemis Project collectables.Precisely what to offer should be worked out in negotiations with theseprofessionals and will depend on their relevant experience and expertise.</P><P>Selling bulk lunar material wholesale means giving up some of thepotential profits. However, doing so would allow taking advantage ofmarketing systems already in existence rather than inventing and buildinga whole new system. It's like the difference between using an <ahref="/adb/04/01/01/01/01/">existinglauncher</a> or building a new launcher. By building a new launcher, theproject would not have to pay the costs that would be profit to thebuilder. But it is worth it to pay this extra money to be dealing withsomebody who has experience in the field.</P><P>Task (1): Identify existing companies that may be interested in marketingmoonrocks and contact them. If none of them are immediately interested inthe concept, find out their concerns (what would it take to get theminterested). Once these concerns are known, future tasks will be developedto try to address these concerns. This, I think, needs to be done bysomebody at an executive level who has intimate knowledge of the entireproject and who has the authority to speak for the company.</P><H3> II. Legal Status of Moonrock Ownership</H3><P>One of the concerns businesses are likely to have is the legal status ofowning moonrocks. If there are any legitimate concerns to be had here,then professional legal council must be sought in order to answer thesequestions. Hopefully, it will be possible to find a licensed professionalwho is interested enough in space travel to do the work for free. If not,then I see no way to avoid the costs of hiring a professional; this is nota job that can be done by an amateur.</P><P>Task (2): A licensed lawyer needs to research the status of moonrockownership. Depending on the results of this research, legal action mayrequired in order to resolve ambiguities in the law.</P><P>Note 1: The legal status of this mission may be able to find precedent inthe legal status of whaling - which, I believe, is done on the high seas.Is there any relevant legal difference between capturing and harvesting awhale on the high seas and capturing and harvesting an asteroid in space?</P><P>Note 2: I think the bulk of the political concerns can be bestillustrated by means of the following hypothetical example: Assume theLunar Prospector discovers a single pocket of water ice. Private ownershipof this resource would be like private ownership of the only oasis in adesert. Under a private ownership scheme, the owner would have the abilityto reap "monopoly prices." The potential income would inevitably lead to afight over who owns it. On earth, these disputes have gotten peoplekilled. If the only way to own it is to take it, then the resource islikely to be squandered and wasted (like the American Buffalo and whales).If nobody can own it - period - then this would be no different than ifthe resource didn't exist at all. It is this type of case, I believe,which will determine the principles governing ownership of items in space.Political agencies should be able to recognize a difference between thisand plain, ordinary moondirt.</P><H3> III. Selling Moonrocks</H3><P>Chances are that companies will need evidence that being involved in thistype of project would be worth the cost. This means stepping into theretail business. With luck, an experienced company would see our fumblingefforts and the money we are receiving in spite of our mistakes andnegotiate a contract to take over the project.</P><P>I would suggest collecting the market for lunar-material collectables inthe following way:</p>.<P>Task (3) Create a small product catalogue. Several ideas have alreadybeen proposed. This, itself, has several small tasks. The display case foreach sample will have to be laid out and designed. Some detailed drawingswould be useful.  Each potential product would need to be researched forcost of production and time involved. Counterfeiting prevention may figurehighly in the costs.</P><P>Task (4) Create prototypes for the material. This is scissors and paper,workbench kind of work using regular earth dirt.</P><P>Task (5) These prototypes should then be "tested." They are shown tofriends, taken to conventions, pictures are posted on the web, and thelike. Input is received which is then used to modify the layout. Newprototypes are then created and tested. The catalogue would have to beupdated as well.</P><P>Task (6) Advance sales. As Greg has argued, a marketing survey is best ifit measures actual behavior. Using the prototypes and the catalogue,marketers should start to collect advance sales. The money received fromthese advance sales should be banked in an interest-bearing account, witha promise to return the money with interest (money-back guarantee) if thegoods can not be delivered. As this account grows, this should attract theinterest of people willing to make a direct investment.</P><P>Important:  This money is not touched until the goods are delivered.Spending the money in advance could be a short road to financial ruin -not to mention the lawsuits generated from people who come to believe thatthe whole thing was a scam. Putting the money in such an account willgo a long way to convincing people that this is serious, and thus likely to contribute to greater sales.</P><P>Still, without touching the money in this account, we can show it topeople and say, "This is what we have already sold. Invest in the project,and after we deliver the product to these people a percentage (to benegotiated) of this and all the other money we make will be yours." Thiscould attract some potential direct investment.  (It could also be used ascollateral for a loan, but this is worse than spending the money.)</P><P>It will be important to listen to the salespeople; who, in turn, have afinancial stake in listening to their customers. They will say what theyneed to sell the material. Give it to them.</P><P>Option: Create two different lines of products; a risk-free product linedescribed above (if we fail, you get your money back with interest), and arisk-taker/investor product line (your money goes into the LunarDevelopment Fund and will be used to finance the mission, or split, withsomething like 20% of the money going into the ASI General Fund and 80%into the Lunar Development Fund. We make no guarantee that the missionwill succeed and you may not get your money back if we fail). The productsshould be different - and risk takers should be allowed to pay somewhatless (say 75%) for comparable products.</P><P>I think it would be a good idea to take advantage of the incentivescreated by commissioned sales. People who are allowed to take 5%-10% offthe top for everything they sell end up selling a whole lot more thanthose who do not. There is a reason why they are so widely used. However,with a "money-back guarantee" it is not possible to pay commissionedsalespeople for their success and still be able to pay back all those whowould be owed money if the mission failed. Proposed solution: Salespeoplecan keep 5% to 10% of the value of everything they sell in the investmentline (since there is no money-back guarantee). This will give thesalespeople an incentive to push the investment line of products.However, salespeople will not get their commission on the risk-free lineuntil the products are delivered and the money is received from thisaccount. Salespeople will then receive their commission plus interest. Ifthis enterprise turns out to be successful enough, we won't need othercompanies.</P><!-- Nav Bar --><hr size="5"><table align=center border=4 cellpadding = 3 cellspacing=2><tr><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/index.html">ArtemisProject</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/asi_index.html">ArtemisSociety</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/adb/index.html">ArtemisData Book</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="/adb/j/index.html">FAQ</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="/adb/04/index.html">Reference Mission</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.tlrc.com/catalog.html">Catalog</a></b></tr></table><hr size="5"><font size=-2>Copyright &#169; 1996 Artemis Society International.Updated Tue, Apr 16, 1996<br>Content by R. Alonzo Fyfe <ahref="mailto:pegasus@indra.com">&lt;pegasus@indra.com&gt;</a>, maintainedby <AHREF="MAILTO:simon@eagle.ca">&lt;simon@eagle.ca&gt;</A>.<br>"<a href="/Artemis.html">The Artemis Project</a>"is a trademark of <aHREF="http://www.tlrc.com/Lrc.html">The Lunar Resources Company</a>.</font></body></html>
