<HTML> <HEAD> <TITLE>3. The Artemis Project as a Commercial Venture</TITLE></HEAD><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><!-- Artemis Data Book section 3. Business of the Artemis Project --><!-- file: /adb/03/corporate-structure.html           /adb/03/05/corporate-structure.html           /adb/06/corporate-structure.html --><!-- Keywords: corporation non-profit sponsor affiliate organizationstructure board --><h2 align="center">Artemis Data Book</H2><h2 align="center">3. Business of the Artemis Project</H2><h2 align="center">Artemis Society International and The Lunar ResourcesCompany</H2><P><HR><P><P><a href="/asi_index.html">ASI</a> and <ahref="http://www.tlrc.com/">LRC</a> are two independent organizations, withdifferent goals and motivations.  They have separate officers, separatebank accounts, and their corporate headquarters are a thousand milesapart.</P><P>Obviously, everyone involved in both organizations is devoted tobuilding this lunar base, and many of the people involved in <ahref="/asi_index.html">Artemis Society International</a> are also part of<a href="http://www.tlrc.com/">The Lunar Resources Company</a>.<P>Artemis Society International is a non-profit scientific and educationalfoundation incorporated in the state of Alabama, headquartered in Huntsville.President and Chairman of the Board of the Artemis Society is J. BoisePearson, who has no affliation with LRC, and doesn't even own stock inLRC. The role of ASI in the Artemis Project is to make the lunar basehappen.</P><P>The Lunar Resources Company is a privately held Texas corporation, and<a href="/bios/bennett.gregory.html">Greg Bennett</a> is its President andChairman of the Board.  LRC started the <a href="/artemis.html">ArtemisProject</a> and underwrote ASI's debts until ASI got on its feetindependently.  LRC's role in the Artemis Project, like every other companyparticipating in this program, is to conduct commercial business which willresult in revenues flowing into the Artemis Society's Lunar BaseDevelopment Fund.  We do that through donations as well as producinglicensed products.  Currently the only products we have on the market arethe "<a href="http://www.tlrc.com/catalog.html">Moonbase Artemis</a>" lineof <a href="http://www.tlrc.com/moonbase.logo.html">coffee mugs</a>, <ahref="http://www.tlrc.com/moonbase.logo.html">T-shirts</a>, and such.  Inthe long run, we plan to develop commercial enterprises on the moon.</P><P>The whole point of starting The Lunar Resources Company was to provide away to demonstrate that commercial business can earn a profit while providingfinancial support to the lunar development project.  The role of privateenterprise in this project is vital -- without it, we cannot garner theeconomic power needed to do it.  We don't hide the fact that we formed thiscompany because we want a moon base, but we also acknowledge that we have toprovide a good return to the stockholders -- better than they'd get frominvesting in other ventures -- or we haven't succeeded.</P><P>The Artemis Society is where donations and volunteer effort go, so thatpeople know their labors will go to developing the moon rather than lining thepockets of a for-profit company.  That's an important distinction: if you dothings for the Artemis Society, it should be donated volunteer effort; butif youdo work for The Lunar Resources Company or any of the other commercial firmsparticipating in the project, you should get paid for it.</P><P>LRC does not anticipate being the company who actually builds thespacecraft.  That's a job better done by an established aerospace company,someone with all the expertise on board and processes in place to do it rightthe first time.</P><P>The Lunar Resources Company has 13 stockholders, of whom three (<ahref="/bios/bennett.gregory.html">Greg Bennett</a>, <ahref="/bios/strock.ian.html">Ian Strock</a>, and <ahref="http://www.acess.digex.het/~dcarson/">Dana Carson</a>, among others)volunteered to serve on the ASI Board of Directors.  Greg Bennett is alsochairman of ASI's Board of Advisors, tasked with building an advisory boardwhich can represent the best knowledge not only in space flight, but alsoin many areas of the entertainment industry.  Remember that financial andbusiness research is as important to the success of the Artemis Project asdesigning a good spaceship.</P><P>None of the <a href="/adb/03/04/">revenues</a> of the Artemis Society goto The Lunar Resources Company, though LRC does provide -- at cost -- someof the Society's material. LRC also wrote the check for ASI's world wideweb site, for which we were reimbursed by the Society.</P><P>LRC has also offered to provide fund-raising goods (T-shirts, coffeecups, etc.) to the Society at discounted wholesale prices.  When LRC sellsthese things at retail, a portion of the retail price goes to ASI.  (It'sactually a rather larger portion than ASI would ask of other companies, butLRC is rather paternal about ASI.)</P><P>There are no secrets here.  Many other <a href="/adb/10/">commercialcompanies</A>, which may earn profits from the Artemis Project, are activelyinvolved in support of the Artemis Society.  Duncan Graphics, a Californiacorporation, also donates material to the Society.  Steve Jackson, of SteveJackson Games, is a founding member of the Society.  Space ResearchAssociates have donated a great deal of research and articles to theSociety.  It would be the same if Musicians Contact Service elected tobecome a sponsor of the Artemis Project.</P><P>Right now you'll see the phrase "The Artemis Project is a trademark ofThe Lunar Resources Company" on a lot of literature.  That's a fact; LRCestablished that trademark long before we started the Artemis Society.  Rightnow we're working out the details of transferring ownership of the trademarksand copyrights to the literature to the Artemis Society.  The issues arecomplicated, but we'll get it all figured out.  The number one most importantissue is making sure that the Artemis Project continues, regardless of whathappens to any of the organizations or companies involved.</P><P>The reason we have this problem with trademarks is that initially wethought the best way to make the <a href="/artemis.html">ArtemisProject</a> happen was by first demonstrating with a regular for-profitcompany that there are profits to be earned in this business, and therebyattracting other commercial enterprises to it.  The idea of a non-profitmembership organization to provide a means for people to participatedirectly in the project came later.</P><P>As the Society developed, it became obvious that the non-profitfoundation is the best vehicle to carry out the Artemis Project.  People aremuch happier about donating their time and talents to it; it enjoysconsiderable tax advantages; and we think that other commercial businesseswill be more willing to support the project if they're not worried aboutsomeone else's profit motive.</P><P>You might be wondering why Greg Bennett isn't President of the ArtemisSociety, since he started this whole thing.  Besides the obvious fact thathe's already overworked, the primary reason is to avoid any potentialconflictof interest, or semblance of a conflict of interest.  He had to choose betweenLRC and ASI. He's done non-profit foundations and big aerospace projects, soLRC seemed like the bigger challenge and growth opportunity.  There's yetanother strong reason -- Boise Pearson is a very wise and patient man, andhe's just as dedicated to carrying out this lunar base project as thefounder.</P><P>We enthusiastically encourage open public discussion of this wholeprocess. We're well aware that leaves us open to all sorts of criticism, andsome of that criticism isn't exactly top-quality advice.  If anyone has goodideas about how to organize this project, how to attract capital to it, how topublicize it, please do <a href="mailto:artemis@asi.org">speak up</a>.(And if you see someone venture what appears to be a silly idea, cut himsome slack!)</P><P>If anyone else has questions about this, please do <ahref="mailto:artemis@asi.org">ask</a>.  Our one goal is to make that moonbase happen.  We need your wisdom as much as your time and talent.</P><!-- Nav Bar --><hr size="5"><table align=center border=4 cellpadding = 3 cellspacing=2><tr><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/index.html">ArtemisProject</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/asi_index.html">ArtemisSociety</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/adb/index.html">ArtemisData Book</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="/adb/j/index.html">FAQ</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="/adb/04/index.html">Reference Mission</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.tlrc.com/catalog.html">Catalog</a></b></tr></table><hr size="5"><font size=-2>Copyright &#169; 1996 Artemis Society International.Updated Wed, March 13, 1996<br>Content by <a href="/bios/bennett.gregory.html">Gregory R. Bennett</a> <ahref="mailto:grb@asi.org">&lt;grb@asi.org&gt;</a>, maintained by <AHREF="MAILTO:simon@eagle.ca">&lt;simon@eagle.ca&gt;</A>.<br><a href="http://www.asi.org/index.html">The Artemis Project</a>is a trademark of <aHREF="http://www.tlrc.com/Lrc.html">The Lunar Resources Company</a>.</font></body></html>
