<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>6.8.7 SSTO Passenger and Support Mass</TITLE></HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<!-- Artemis Data Book -->
<!-- ADB section 6.8.7 SSTO Concept Design Project Team-->
<!-- file: /adb/06/08/07/passenger-support-mass.html -->
<!-- Keywords: ssto lunar tourism passenger mass weight support systems  -->
<!-- v 1.0 -->
<h2 align="center">Artemis Data Book</H2>
<h2 align="center">6.8.7 SSTO Concept Design Project Team</H2>
<h2 align="center">SSTO Passenger and Support Mass</H2>
<P ALIGN=CENTER><I>Gregory R. Bennett</I></P>
<P><HR><P>

<BLOCKQUOTE><table>
<tr><th><B>Component</B></th><th><B>Mass in lbm</B></th></tr>
<tr><td>Passenger and baggage</td><td>165</td></tr>
<tr><td>Emergency gear</td><td>40</td></tr>
<tr><td>ELCS equipment</td><td>20</td></tr>
<tr><td>Total Consumables</td><td>55</td></tr>
<tr><td>Seat</td><td>42</td></tr>
<tr><td><B>Total</B></td><td>322</td></tr>
</table></BLOCKQUOTE>

<P>A 150-passenger airliner has 3 flight attendants, a ratio of 1:50. So
it's not unreasonable to assume 4 flight attendants for 50 people. That
lets the attendants work in shifts (it's a long flight) at a ratio of 
1:25, plus the two pilots. We have to assume our passengers will have a 
bit of horse sense and enough training to survive the trip.</P>

<P>So, with 56 people and the above requirements, the total mass is:</P>

<BLOCKQUOTE><table>
<tr><td><B>Component</B></td><td><B>Mass in lbm</B></td></tr>
<tr><td>Passenger and baggage</td><td>9240</td></tr>
<tr><td>Emergency gear</td><td>2240</td></tr>
<tr><td>ELCS equipment</td><td>1120</td></tr>
<tr><td>Total Consumables</td><td>3080</td></tr>
<tr><td>Seat</td><td>2352</td></tr>
<tr><td><B>Total</B></td><td>18032</td></tr>
</table></BLOCKQUOTE>

