<!-- V 2.0 Pleiades 4 --><HTML>
<HEAD> <TITLE>Pleiades Issue IV</TITLE> </HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<IMG SRC="http://www.asi.org/Gifs/artlogona.gif" align="top"><font size=-2>TM</font><BR>
<H1>Pleiades Issue #4</H1>
<H3>The Newsletter of the Artemis Society</H3>
<P><HR><P>

<P>Pleiades is now part of the <a href="/mmm">Moon Miner's Manifesto</a>, which is hosted in the <a href="/index.html">Artemis Project</a> <a href="/adb/09/04/01/">web site</a>. <a href="/mmm">Check there</a> for the newest issues!</P>

<P><HR><P>
<UL>
	<LI><B><A HREF="#D_ticket">A &quot;D&quot; Ticket?</A></B>
	<LI><B><A HREF="#Artemis_95">Artemis '95</A></B>
	<LI><B><A HREF="#documentary">Lights! Camera! Nonfiction!</A></B>
	<LI><B><A HREF="#alt_missions">Alternative Missions for the Lunar Transfer Vehicle</A></B>
	<LI><B><A HREF="#ltv">Changes to the LTV?</A></B>
	<LI><B><A HREF="huntsville.html">Artemis '95: The Huntsville Conference</A></B>
	<LI><B><A HREF="#news">News Cruise</A></B>
</UL>

<P><HR><P>

<H3 align=center><A NAME="D_ticket">A &quot;D&quot; Ticket?</a></H3>
<P>Over the years, the Delta series of launch vehicles from McDonnell
Douglas have been one of the most reliable tickets for both commercial and
government flights. A new generation of Delta vehicles may provide another
<a href="/adb/04/01/01/01/01/comparison-table.html">potential vehicle</a> for Artemis.</P>

<P> The Delta III more than doubles the capacity of its predecessor.  Where a
Delta II could deliver 4,100 lbs. to geosynch, the Delta III should be able to
place 8,400 lbs in geosynchronous orbit.  This brings it into the range of
vehicles that could deliver Artemis crews and vehicles to space.</P>

<P> But will the new vehicle be man-rated?  Maybe not for NASA, but McDonnell's
Sr. Vice President for Space, Dr. Bill Olsen, sees no reason that the Delta III
could not be used in manned launches.  According to Dr. Olsen, the Delta family
is the most reliable launcher in the world, with 49 successful launches in a row
and over 250 successful launches overall.  The Delta II has a perfect, 100%
launch record.</P>

<P> Hughes has signed on to use the Delta III in future satellite launches, and
McDonnell sees more and more of their business coming from private launches with decreasing revenues from NASA.</P>

<P> Though the shuttle is still the star of most Artemis plans, the availability
of other launchers provides a great deal of flexibility.  The Delta III is only
one of several potential vehicles which could play a role if the shuttle proves
unsuited or unavailable for all the necessary tasks.</P>

<P><HR><P> 
<H3 align=center><A NAME="Artemis_95">Artemis '95</A></H3>

<P>No, it's not some long-delayed software program.  It's a conference and get
together for everyone involved in or interested in the <a href="/index.html">Artemis Project</a>.</P>

<P> This July, <a href="/asi_index.html">Artemis Society</a> members, along with interested non-members, from
all over the country will gather in Huntsville, Alabama for a conference to
discuss all aspects of the Artemis Project. </P>

<P> Dates for the conference are set as:</P>
 
<P>   <EM>20-23 July 1995</EM></P>
 
<P> Huntsville is the &quot;birthplace of manned spaceflight.&quot; With some of
the best space oriented museums and exhibits in the world within a few miles, and
all conference attendees should have plenty to see and do. Take this opportunity
to put a face with the names you hear from this newsletter or email.  For more
information on the conference,  <A HREF="huntsville.html">get all the details
from Artemis '95</A>.</P>

<font size=2><P>Note: <a href="/artemis96.html">Artemis 96</a> is now under way, and will be held in Houston.</a></font>

<P><HR><P>
<H3 align=center><A NAME="documentary">Lights! Camera! Nonfiction!</A></H2>

<H4 align=center>(Can we really make money from a documentary?)</H4>
 
<P> Perhaps the most unique feature of the Artemis plan is the idea of <a href="/adb/03/04">making
money</a> from the entertainment value of space travel and lunar exploration.  While
much of this revenue will be generated by fictional drama based around the actual
activities of Artemis, nonfiction documentaries have always been intended to play
a part in boosting the total return.</P>

<P> The 1994 film <I>Hoop Dreams</I> has shown that there continues to be
an interest in Documentaries on the big screen.  But how much money can we expect to bring in from these nonfiction films?  With a handful of statistics from a recent issue of the industry publication Variety and a little research, it's
possible to get a pretty good picture of documentaries' money-making ability.</P>

<P> The news is definitely mixed.  On the one hand, documentaries account for
less than 1/3 of 1% of film revenue over the years.  But films make a lot of
money. Within that tiny fraction of total revenues, there is still room for
considerable income.</P>

<P> One of the surprises is how much of a &quot;layer cake&quot; the results
show.  With amazing consistency, documentaries can be slotted into broad
categories that have a direct relationship to their take.</P>

<P> Such quirky fare as <I>Roger and Me</I>, a highly self referential film
about attempts to interview the chairman of GM, pulled down $6.7 million over a
decade ago. There are a number of such off the wall films in the $5-10 million
dollar range.</P>

<P> The middle ranks of the documentary money makers are filled with films with
an outdoor setting.  Remember a man, a beach, and the search for the perfect
wave? <I>Endless Summer</I> brought in $10 million at the box office, and has since made more on TV.  It's also spurred a sequel.</P>

<P> More traditional nature documentaries have also done well.  Before these
shows became a staple of television, big budget nature shows were common on the
big screen.  <I>The Vanishing Wilderness</I> cleared $17 million, and is
the champion of this division.</P>

<P> The next chunk of documentaries have something to do with space travel, but a
lot more to do with quackery.  In the wake of the best-selling book, a film
version of <I>Chariots of the Gods</I> pulled down $25 million.  Right on
its heels was another film about the Bermuda Triangle.  These films were released
while the subject of these books were still &quot;hot,&quot; and show how
documentaries can be effective when played in combination with other media.</P>

<P> Though it only missed being a 70's event by only a couple of months,
<I>Woodstock</I> is still considered by many as the defining moment of 60's
culture. It's not surprising that the film version of this event did good
business in theaters, bringing in $34 million.  Inspired in part by this film's
success, other documentaries on the Beatles, Rolling Stones, and other groups
have brought in similar amounts.</P>

<P> To go much above this level, to reach the top of the charts, a documentary
needs a gimmick.  And the best gimmick of all for luring people into the theater
is to give the viewer something that goes beyond the normal cinema experience. 
Just as 3D glasses bumped up the income for <I>Creature from the Black Lagoon</I>, and rigged seating brought audiences to <I>The Tingler</I>, gimmicks have helped documentaries break out of the pack.</P>

<P> The king of gimmick theater is the 50's hit <I>This Is Cinearama</I>. 
The film was produced at a point when movies were first starting to be shown on
television, and theater owners were perceiving TV as a threat to their existence.
 In response, they tried to show that TV was limited, presenting a tiny, black
and white image that could never match movies.  To play up the difference between
the home and theater experience, this film was shot using special techniques and
played back on oversized, extra-wide screens.  Audiences found the first person
footage of Cinearama exhilarating -- a fact not lost on the designers of modern
interactive cinema and rides like Universal's <I>Back to the Future</I>. 
Even in theaters not equipped with the special screens, and in a time when the
average ticket price was fifty cents, Cinearama raked in $41 million, making it
the biggest grossing picture of the year, and arguably the most successful
documentary ever shown in theaters.</P>

<P> So is that the limit?  Adjusted for inflation, Cinearama's income would
represent a sizable amount of money.  But to find the real champ of documentary
dollars, you need to turn to another gimmick -- IMAX.</P>

<P> For those that have never been to an IMAX theater, the experience is far
different from that found at the local 12-plex.  IMAX film is several times
larger than normal film, and of higher resolution.  It's projected by an extra
bright bulb.  It runs through the projector at a much higher speed.  The result
of all this is a much clearer, more detailed picture.  The higher speed also
helps to make motion more effective, and allows some shots that scream
&quot;fake&quot; when done with normal movie gear.</P>

<P> In older IMAX theaters, the screen is 2-4x the usual theater screen, and
slightly warped to preserve the perspective of the optics in the IMAX system. 
Newer IMAX theaters have screens as much as six stories tall that are warped
around more than 180 degrees both vertically and horizontally.  They are also
equipped with 3D sound systems and speakers of tremendous power.</P>

<P> If you never made it to Kennedy for the launch of a shuttle, experiencing
that launch through IMAX -- with the bass pounding your stomach and making your
teeth vibrate -- is the next best thing.</P>

<P> It's not surprising that audiences have been flocking to IMAX ever since it's
premiere 20 years ago.  There are now 120 IMAX theaters in the United States. 
Many of them are associated with museums, science centers, or parks.  While a
few, like the screen at the Grand Canyon IMAX, play the same bill day after day,
most screens rotate through the slowly growing selection of IMAX films, changing
titles every few months.</P>

<P> The result gives IMAX films two important boosts in the monetary arena:
audiences come just to see the process, and IMAX films stay around year after
year.  With this is mind, it's not surprising that the champion IMAX film is also
the overall top documentary money maker.</P>

<P> <I>To Fly</I>, introduced 19 years ago, is only 27 minute long.  But it's take is
$83 million strong.  Several IMAX films using footage from the shuttle are also
in the upper ranks, earning over $50 million.</P>

<P> The strong performance of IMAX films in general and space-related films in
particular, make a good argument for producing Artemis in this format.  But
things might be changing in IMAX-land.  A new IMAX theater in New York is now
screening the first drama scripted especially for this format.  More IMAX fiction
pieces are in production, and these theaters may soon be less tied to nonfiction
material.  Besides, to get the kind of audience we want, it may be that IMAX is
too old.  Artemis should keep a look out for emerging technologies that might be
the next advance in film viewing.</P>

<P> And if all of these numbers look a bit low, keep in mind that these are
strictly the box office numbers.  Video and broadcast rights can easily raise the
value of the documentaries over $100 million. </P>

<P><HR><P>
<H3 align=center><A NAME="alt_missions">Alternative Missions for the Lunar Transfer Vehicle</A></H3>
   
<font size=2>by  Gregory Bennett</font>
 
<H4>Lunar Transfer Vehicle Requirements</H4>
<P> The primary mission of the Artemis Project's <a href="/adb/04/02/01/ltv-notes.html">Lunar Transfer Vehicle</a> (LTV) is to move the crew and their
spacecraft between low Earth orbit and lunar orbit.  We must be able to reuse the
LTV for several missions, and for a variety of crew sizes from two to six people. 
This mission sets the basic requirements for the LTV.</P>

<P> In the reference mission, the LTV is based on the <a href="/adb/04/03/06/01/">Spacehab module</a>.  By removing all the module of the node that we
didn't need for the mission, we got rid of the great majority of the node's dry
weight.  (Dry weight is the mass of the vehicle when you leave out all the
fuel.)</P>

<P> Then we added some rockets for the main propulsion system and maneuvering,
and additional systems for propulsion, electrical power, thermal control, and
life support.  The node already has the internal equipment needed for controlling
all these systems, but external sensors and antennas have to be added for
guidance, navigation, and communication.</P>
 
<P> <IMG SRC="/Gifs/ltv_m_01.GIF">  <EM>Lunar Transfer Vehicle</EM></P>

<P> This simplified diagram from the reference mission shows the basic concept.
The actual reference vehicle looks more like a cylinder with a rocket nozzle at
one end.  The body-mounted solar power cells and radiators, antennas, and
maneuvering rockets are mounted on ring-shaped service modules attached fore and aft of the pressurized crew compartment.  The LTV is about 15 feet in overall
diameter.</P>

<P> The performance of a rocket system is measured in how much it can accelerate
a given payload.  In engineering terms, we refer to the change in velocity as
delta D.  Engineering shorthand for as delta V is DV, using the Greek letter
delta (D) as the symbol for change.  (In fact, D is the universal symbol for
engineering. Remember what Scotty said in the first Star Trek movie: &quot;I know
engineers; they love to change things!&quot;)</P>

<P> If you add up all the rocket burns needed to get from Earth orbit to an orbit
60 nautical miles above the moon, you get about 13,500 feet per second.  That
defines the LTV's propulsion requirements: it must be able to impart a DV of
13,500 ft/sec to the entire Artemis stack (about 80,000 pounds of spacecraft and
crew when it starts out from Earth orbit, about the weight of two railroad
engines). Then, after the crew has done their work on the moon, it must again
handle a DV of 13,500 ft/sec to get itself, the crew, and the Ascent Stage
vehicle (about 7,000 pounds total dry weight, a couple of mid-sized automobiles)
back from lunar orbit to an orbit around the Earth. </P>

<P> The LTV must be able to keep the crew alive and comfortable for at least six
days (three days out, three days back) of active use, and remain unattended in
lunar orbit for several weeks while the crew works on the surface of the moon. 
Because of the nature of the Artemis Project, the LTV has to support very high
data rates with its communications systems' two channels of compressed
high-resolution video.  So it has the radio power of a small communications
satellite.</P>

<P> The basic concept for refueling the LTV is to replace its empty fuel tanks
with full ones in low Earth orbit.  For the first few missions at least, the
spacecraft will be refueled with full tanks brought up from earth's surface.  The
empty tanks will be stored in Earth orbit so they can be reused later, refilled
with hydrogen from Earth and <a href="/adb/04/03/10/04/oxygen-exraction.html">oxygen</a> shipped in from the moon.</P>
 
<P><HR><P>
<H3 align=center>Other Missions for the LTV</H3>

<P> Given all that the LTV can do, it begs the question, what else might we do
with it?</P>

<H4> Earth orbit research laboratory.</H4>
<P> Since the LTV's docking mechanisms are
compatible with those used on the International Space Station, it can be attached
to the space station for use as additional laboratory space.  Its interior
outfitting will accommodate standard space station payload racks, and its windows provide opportunities for Earth observation. </P>

<H4>LEO free-flyer.</H4>
<P> The LTV can also fly free in low Earth orbit, supporting its
crew for a week or more of Earth observation.  During these missions it can also
be used in conjunction with NASA's manned maneuvering unit to recover or repair
satellites in low Earth orbit with no modification. </P>
 
<H4>Geosynchronous satellite servicing</H4>
<P> Geosynchronous orbit is that circular orbit around the Earth where we park
most of our communications satellites.  Flying a crew to and from geosynchronous
orbit is certainly within the propulsion capabilities of the LTV; however there
is a problem: Earth's radiation belts.  In its reference mission, the LTV passes
through the radiation belts very quickly, exposing the crew to a maximum dose of
1 REM of radiation.  To put that into perspective, NASA's 30-day exposure limit
is 25 REM.  Workers on Earth are limited to 5 REM/year, and the median lethal
dose is 450 REM.  To remain for any length of time inside the radiation belts,
the crew will have to be heavily shielded.  Even their space suits will require
extra shielding. This doesn't make it impossible to service communications
satellites in geosynchronous orbit, but it does mean additional development and
experimentation will be required before we can commit the LTV this kind of
mission.</P>
 
<H4> Near-Earth Asteroids</H4>
<P> Hundreds, perhaps thousands, of metal-rich asteroids orbit the sun near the
Earth.  An article in  the Journal of Geophysical Research estimated that a
kilometer-sized metal bearing Near-Earth Asteroid contains up to 400,000 metric
tons of platinum-group metals.  Those metals would command a price of 5 trillion
dollars at current U. S. market prices; however, the article points out that
flooding the market with this much metal would reduce the market value to 320
billion dollars.  That's still an incredible economic incentive to explore these
asteroids. The DV required to rendezvous with and explore a near-Earth asteroid
is actually less than that required to land on the moon. The mission would be
longer -- perhaps as long as nine months -- so the logistics of providing life
support for the crew become more complex.  We would want to add closed-loop
systems for water and atmosphere.  The total vehicle weight grows, and with the
fuel requirements.  The additional fuel can be accommodated in strap-on tanks,
located over the crew compartment to provide additional radiation shielding. In
contrast to the geosynchronous orbit mission, radiation is less of a problem for
an asteroid exploration flight.  The primary radiation concern is the Galactic
Cosmic Radiation dose the crew will receive, with the additional likelihood of an
anomalously large solar flare event.  The crew can be protected from a solar
flare by providing a region of massive shielding -- most likely the main engine
compartment with all its tanks and plumbing -- which can be oriented toward the
incoming proton flux.</P>
 
<H4>Circumlunar flight</H4>
<P> Finally, one proposed mission for the LTV can be carried out with no
modification at all to the vehicle: a trip to lunar orbit similar to that of
Apollo 8.  While it has been done before, it hasn't been done for a long time,
and we will be able to make this exciting flight even before the other Artemis
vehicles are completed.  In addition to generating a tremendous amount of
publicity for the project, such a flight would be a shake-down cruise for the
LTV, the crew, and the flight support team here on Earth.</P>

<P><HR><P>
<H3 align=center><A NAME="ltv">Changes to the LTV?</A></H3>

<P>Like all the rest of the vehicles that make up the Artemis &quot;stack,&quot;
the LTV is a long way from its final version.  Recently, a lot of number
crunching has been going on that indicates some changes might have to be made in
the design and operation of the LTV.</P>

<P>Current plans call for the LTV to act as the delivery vehicle that will bring
the lunar habit to lunar orbit during our first mission.  However, this places
extraordinary requirements on the LTV in its first mission as it has to transport
a mass much greater than it will in ordinary earth to moon shuttle service.</P>

<P>One possibility would be to trim the functionality of the LTV back to a
simple ferry, and provide some seperate, perhaps expendable, booster to carry the
habitat core into place.  The LTV could then make do with smaller engines and
fuel tanks, and would be less expensive to build and launch.</P>

<P>However, if the LTV was trimmed back to the minimum requirements for crew
transport, it would no longer be capable of some of the extended missions
discussed in the previous article.  And it would be unable to deliver a second
habitat module when needed.</P>

<P>Stay tuned, and feel free to send your comments and discussion on the
subject. </P>

<P><HR><P>
<H3 align=center><A NAME="news">News Cruise</A></H3>
<H4 ALIGN=CENTER>News of Interest to Artemis Society Members</H4>
<P><font size=2>compiled by Cynthia Griffin of Space Research Associates in
Houston</font></P>

<H4>European Community in Space</H4>
<P> Later this year the European Space Agency will further consider their lunar
exploration initiative. ESA representatives have been &quot;enthusiastic about
the rich opportunities offered by the exploration and utilization of the
Moon&quot; and have proposed a &quot;phased approach&quot; for such a plan.  In
contrast to NASA's &quot;faster-cheaper-better&quot; mode, European engineers
were directed to inject more up-front cost and technology discipline to their
lunar lander program.  At this time it is not certain whether the phased approach
of the lunar initiative will include manned mission in later phases.</P>
 
<H4>The way it used to be</H4>
<P>After the Apollo 11 lunar landing, Wernher von Braun's plan was to have a
six-person station orbiting the Moon by 1975. This would be followed in five
years by a six-person lunar surface base.  By 1990 von Braun had hoped to have 24
people in lunar orbit and 48 people living on the surface of the Moon engaged in
mining, astronomy, biology, selenology (lunar geology), seismology, regional
exploration, and planetary quarantine.  The planetary quarantine facility would
be used for martian samples from the semipermanent Mars base that von Braun hoped would be operational at the same time as the more permanent lunar base.</P>
 
<H4>Great Haul of China</H4>
<P>China's space plan for the next five years includes a satellite to orbit the
Moon near the year 2000.  &quot;China's space technology now has the capacity to
probe the Moon,&quot; said Jiang Jingshan, director of the Space Centre of the
Chinese Academy of Sciences.  Studies are underway to determine the scope of the
lunar mission after preliminary optical and microwave remote sensing satellites
are placed in Earth orbit.  China earlier announced it planned to place its first
astronaut in orbit around 2000.</P>

<H4>Who you gonna call?</H4>
<P> Scientists at the Los Alamos National Laboratory have linked the levels of
high-energy electrons encircling Earth to the solar cycle and are offering their
data to help satellite designers.  According to Richard Belian of Los Alamos, the
biggest threat to spacecraft is not during the Sun's most intensely active part
of its 11-year cycle (solar maximum) as many had believed, but about one year
before solar minimum.  Since the next solar minimum will occur in 1996, the
threat of solar radiation trapped in the Earth's magnetosphere is now high.  As
more electronics are added to satellites, the issue of shielding from damaging
radiation is growing in importance.</P>
 
<H4>An Oscar-winning name</H4>
<P> Actor Tom Hanks, awarded an Oscar for <I>Forrest Gump</I> and now portraying
astronaut Jim Lovell in the movie <I>Apollo 13</I>, has his own production company in
Century City, California.  It's not unusual for actors to get into the movie
production side of the business, but what is unusual is the name of Hanks'
company:  Cla Vius Base.  Asked to explain, Hanks was quoted in Daily Variety: 
&quot;It's from <I>2001: A Space Odyssey</I>.  When that came out in 1968, I couldn't
sleep the night before.  It was the first time I was moved in a different way by
a movie. The character in the movie was going to Cla Vius Base in a moon bus. 
It's also the name of the biggest crater on the moon.  Also, it's a goofy name I
had come up with to name my production company.&quot;</P>
 
<H4>Coming to an Earth theater near you</H4>
<P>&quot;Space&quot; seems to be the word for movies nowadays as the production
company Lion's Share Inc. continues working on its project called <I>Helium 3,
Power to Rule the World</I>.  The story takes place in 2025 when people live
in a violent society where poverty prevails, the ozone layer is gone, and fossil
fuels are completely depleted.  <a href="/adb/02/09/he3-intro.html">Helium 3</a> from the Moon is believed to be the only
chance of saving Earth.  The reluctant hero Steven Webb has to battle the evil
Megatech, the world's largest corporation, which is monopolizing the Helium 3
market and holding the world hostage.  The movie began production last year.</P>
 
<H4>Home down under</H4>
<P> A group called Oregon Moonbase is running lunar-base simulations in lava
caves located around Bend, Oregon.  The idea is to test the feasibility of using
lunar lava flow tubes to place habitat modules below the surface of the Moon. 
First suggested by NASA scientist Friedrich Horz in 1985, using lunar lava tubes
for moon bases would help shield residents from cosmic and solar flare radiation.
The group proposes using light, inflatable habitation modules that would fit into
the long narrow tunnels.  Good news for homemakers:  researchers believe the
lunar lava tubes won't be as dusty as the Oregon caves.</P>
 
<H4>Mister, can you paradigm?</H4>
<P> Richard Hoagland, former space consultant to NBC and CBS News, is probably
more well known today as the guy who believes in the &quot;Face on Mars.&quot; 
For over 11 years, Hoagland has been campaigning across the country trying to get
scientists to seriously consider that an advanced civilization once lived on
Mars.  In his book <I>The Monuments of Mars</I>,  he describes his belief
that intelligence-built structures on Mars and the Moon are linked to structures
on Earth and that they are all tied together by an advanced new physics he
describes as &quot;hyperdimensional.&quot;  Hoagland's campaign has led him to
even address the United Nations, but to no avail.  What does Hoagland do in his
spare time?  He raises funds for private missions to the moon or Mars with the
hope of proving his theories.</P>
 
<H4>Here comes the Sun</H4>
<P> The Suntracker program tracks the Sun from a given position on the Moon. 
Computer programmers Warren Woods and Dustin Spires of NASA's Marshall Space
Flight Center developed the Suntracker program which computes the selenographic
(moon-centered) position of the Sun at a given Julian date, then converts the
selenographic position of the Sun into azimuth and elevation at the given
position on the Moon based on the lunar equatorial plane.  The program has its
limits, however.  The orbital elements used do not account for nutation,
aberration, and precession.  And the selenographic coordinates computed by the
program are based on 1961 algorithms which have since been updated.  Yet when
compared with computations based on newer values, the programmers report average deviations in selenographic longitude and latitude computed by Suntracker were less than 0.02 deg.</P>
 
<H4>Now in print</H4>
<P> The new book <I>Free Space!  Real Alternatives for Reaching Outer
Space</I> is a good read for the person interested in space but who may
believe NASA is the only ball game in town.  The book introduces the growing
alternative to government-sponsored space exploration - the private commercial
space movement. Written by B. Alexander Howerton, the book includes a general
introduction and overview of <A HREF="http://www.asi.org/Artemis.html">The
Artemis Project</A>.  <I>Free Space!</I> is available directly from the
publisher, <A HREF="gopher://gopher.well.com/00/Business/catalog.asc">Loompanics
Unlimited</A>, P. O. Box 1197, Port Townsend, WA  98368. </P>

