Last-modified: Tue, 16 Apr 1996 15:06:43 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>9. Document Revision Numbering System</TITLE></HEAD><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><!-- Artemis Data Book --><!-- ADB section 9. Electronic Communication --><!-- file: /adb/09/document-revision-format.html --><!-- Keywords: document paper essay updates current up-to-date numberingsystem format conventions --><!-- v 1.0 --><h2 align="center">Artemis Data Book</H2><h2 align="center">9. Electronic Communication</H2><h2 align="center">Document Revision Numbering System</H2><P><HR><P><P>Our current document numbering systemassumes we publish paper, and only paper.  Meanwhile, 99.99% of what we'republishing is electronic.</P><P>By the very nature of the internet, all files are subject to revision,unlike paper editions. Adding a revision letter when we make editorialchanges to a givenformat for a document, and updating the rev number when we make asubstantial change in the content appears to be the best approach toorganising inevitable updates.</P><P>Let's design this with the mission in mind: Why track revisions todocuments?</P><ol><LI><P>So someone using a document can determine if this is the       latest version.</P><LI><P>So the book boss can determine what changes were made for       what reason, and go back to old revisions if necessary.</P><LI><P>So people contributing information to the document will see      what changes others have made, and determine if their work is       affected by other changes.  That is, page change notices (or       perhaps section change notices) highlight changes so that       everyone using that information will be notified that a change       has occurred.</P><LI><P>So we can do an impact assessment.  If a change looks like       it will affect others' work, we should distribute a proposed       change before accepting it.  This allows others to determine how       the change will affect what they're doing; and then the sundry       product teams and managers can decide whether this change is       worth implementing.</P></OL><P>So there should be a common identifier that changes when the <I>content</I>of a document changes, as well as an identifier for editorial changes thatdon't affect the content.  For instance, in a <ahref="/adb/j/">document</a> defining the<a href="/adb/04/">Reference Mission</a>, switching from space stationmodules to <a href="/adb/04/03/06/01/">SPACEHAB modules</a>is a significant change; while changing the spelling from "Spacehab" to"SPACEHAB" is an editorial change.</P><P>If a user picks up rev 20 of a given document, he should know thatregardless of the format, the information contained in that document is thesame in the rev 20 he'll see on the web or in an electronic Word Perfectfile.  Formatting and editorial nits may vary, but the basic information isthe same.  An important part of that information is the outline -- anychange to the outline constitutes a major change to a document because whenuser refers to section 5.3.6, he should not be sending someone to an essayon farming when he's talking about hypergolic propellants.</P><P>Mostly, we can track these through the filename extensions: '.wp' forWord Perfect, '.msw' for Microsoft Word, '.txt' for plain text, '.html' forHTML.  To accommodate older operating systems, we probably do not want togo to a decimal system of tracking editorial changes such as "r20.1.msw".That leaves us with your original suggestion: add a letter for editorialchanges specific to a given format.</P><P>Each document should have a book boss who tells everyone when asubstantial change is made, as well as a designated maintainer for eachformat who updates the document in his format when the book boss approves amajor change.  If the maintainer fixes some editorial nits, he'll incrementthe revision letter without worrying about what other folks are doing.  Sor20a.msw might not be exactly the same as r20a.wp or r20a.html, but atleast all those r20's contain the same information.</P><P>In the printed documents and electronic files, we can track revnumbers on the title page, lists of active pages, revision history, andwhatnot.  But for the web documents, this sounds like yet another item toput in small type in the footer.</P><!-- Nav Bar --><hr size="5"><table align=center border=4 cellpadding = 3 cellspacing=2><tr><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/index.html">ArtemisProject</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/asi_index.html">ArtemisSociety</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/adb/index.html">ArtemisData Book</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="/adb/j/index.html">FAQ</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="/adb/04/index.html">Reference Mission</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.tlrc.com/catalog.html">Catalog</a></b></tr></table><hr size="5"><font size=-2>Copyright &#169; 1996 Artemis Society International.Updated Tue, Apr 16, 1996<br>Content by <a href="/bios/bennett.gregory.html">Gregory R. Bennett</a> <ahref="mailto:grb@asi.org">&lt;grb@asi.org&gt;</a>, maintained by <AHREF="MAILTO:simon@eagle.ca">&lt;simon@eagle.ca&gt;</A>.<br>"<a href="/Artemis.html">The Artemis Project</a>"is a trademark of <aHREF="http://www.tlrc.com/Lrc.html">The Lunar Resources Company</a>.</font></body></html>
