<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>9.4.1 Web Site Access Statistics Notes</TITLE></HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<!-- Artemis Data Book -->
<!-- ADB section 9.4.1 Artemis Project Web Site -->
<!-- file: /adb/09/04/01/access-statistics-notes.html -->
<!-- v 1.0 -->
<h2 align="center">Artemis Data Book</H2>
<h2 align="center">9.4.1 Artemis Project Web Site</H2>
<h2 align="center">Web Site Access Statistics Notes</H2>
<P ALIGN=CENTER><I>Gregory R. Bennett</I></P>
<P><HR><P>

<P>It is important to track web site access statistics so we can assemble a
historical graph. These metrics would be very valuable. Besides provding
fodder for charts to impress the visitor to the ASI site, those historical
data will provide the Artemis Project with valuable management data:</P>

<ul type=circle>
 <li>whether we're growing or stagnating, or even driving people away
 <li>which articles are most popular (good marketing data)
 <li>number of impressions each article gets (for selling advertising
       and attracting big sponsors to the Artemis Project)
 <li>effectiveness of sundry advertising campaigns
 <li>how much the technical teams are using the on-line resources
       (so we can decide if they're worth doing)
 <li>whether users can find the information they're looking for (an
       important common reference page that doesn't get very many hits
       when lots of folks should be looking it up is probably too hidden)
 <li>effectiveness of getting listed in sundry search engines
 <li>effectiveness of links from other web sites
 <li>frequency of hits from non-Anglophone countries (to decide whether
       we need to invest resources in translating the pages into Japanese
       or Sanskrit; and whether we should emphasize the international
       nature of the project or downplay it)
 <li>Relative number of hits from ISP's who cater to the home user vs.
       business, government, and educational users
<li>Number of accesses from organizations that run related programs,
       such as ESA, NASA, NASDA, RSA, universities</ul>

<P>For example, given a large enough body of information, we can decide
whether it's really true that the greatest appeal of the project is "you
can go, too." If folks visit pretty pictures of the lunar community but
very few visit the "how you get to go" parts, we'll get a hint that the
adventure story is more important than the reality of being able to go
there yourself.</P>

<P>One graph I'd like to see: historical growth in number of hits vs. 
time since we started the web site. Perhaps another curve normalizing that
information by dividing by the number of households with web site access. 
Both the growth trend and the bumps on the curve would be very telling. 
For instance, AOL recently upgraded their browser big time, and of course
we had the release of Windows 95 with the new Microsoft browser. Did those
have any effect on the number of people visiting our site?</P>


