<HTML><HEAD> <TITLE>4. Units of Measure</TITLE> </HEAD><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><!-- Artemis Data Book section 4. Reference Mission --><!-- file: /adb/04/units.html --><!-- Keywords: metric SI imperial british units measurement measureinternational units of measure flames are annoying --><h2 align="center">Artemis Data Book</H2><h2 align="center">4. Reference Mission</H2><h2 align="center">Units of Measure</H2><P><HR><P><P>    It's not a matter of U. S. chauvism, or any other pejoratives onemight apply in promoting the metric system; it's a matter of money.  Youshould work in whatever units you're comfortable with.  We mix units betweenthe two systems all the time, and once in a while make jokes about it inscience fiction stories.  For most applications, the whole issue wasovercome decades ago by the invention of the $3.00 four-functioncalculator.  But when it comes to writing certain chunks of software andacquiring certain bits of hardware, we're going to have to use Englishunits.</P><P>     Let's get real here.  We're not going to redesign and recertifyavionics just because the existing boxes happen to fit a rack built toround numbers of English units.  We're not going to custom-manufactureevery bolt to have metric threads and an English head.  We're not going torewrite, debug, and recertify ten million lines of code.</P><P>     If someone feels so strongly about the metric system that he iswilling to donate several billion dollars to the cause so that we canredesign and retool and reprogram the world's industrial base, then let'stalk about it.  If not, we'll put the whole issue on the shelf with all theother social engineering campaigns and get on with the space flightprogram.</P><P>     The most important issue about systems of units for the ArtemisProject is to establish the units we'll use to express length, force, mass,and so on.  We can list tables in both metric and English units, but wedefinitely do not want to have to list half a dozen different metricsystems.  For example, if we're going to talk about mass in metric units,let's use kilograms.  The beauty of the metric system is its consistency;its worst fault is the lack of consistency in how people use it.</P><P>     For instance, when engineers report pressure in the English system,they use pounds per square inch; but when you read reports from ESA, CSA,NASDA, and RSA you never know <I>what</I> you're going to get.  There's no wayto get a feel for the numbers.  It varies among groups within organizationswithin companies within agencies within countries.  What shall we use forpressure?  Pascals (newtons per square meter), or dynes per squarecentimeter, or BAR (which BAR?), or kilograms per square millimeter,atmospheres, or what?  The most useful measurement would be kg/m^2; itconverts directly to the units that matter for designing the system, eventhough talking about kilograms of force drives some folks crazy.</P><P>     When it comes to communication, our crew will be familiar enough withthe numbers and with each other that it doesn't matter.  They'll developtheir own language anyway.  Our job as reporters of these events is tocommunicate with and entertain our audience.  If we have to talk about thesize of a crater we'll tell them in whatever language they speak,regardless of what the government thinks, perhaps with a bit of foreignunits thrown in to maintain the exotic flavor of the adventure.</P><P>     None of this means we don't have sympathy for people who worship themetric system.  We've done time at that alter, too.  We used the metricsystem all through college, in every science course and in most engineeringcourses; everything we knew about science and engineering was calibrated inmetric units.  However, the day we graduated from college we were in for amajor learning experience.  In the real engineering world, where peopleactually make things instead of just doing theoretical calculations, theyuse the English sytem unless coerced by their government to use the metricsystem.</P><P>     Incidentally, the official U. S. government policy of forcing peopleto use the metric system ended with President Carter's administration.Ever since then it has been a matter of personal choice, except ongovernment contracts.  The social engineers still force us to spend a hugepotful of your money studying the question with every contract, but theanswer always comes out the same.</p><P>     Even with participation from the European Space Agency, the CanadianSpace Agency, the National Space Development Agency of Japan, and theRussians, we have not been able to identify any real advantage forswitching to the metric system.  The disadvantage is the horrendous cost.</P><P>     Footnote 1: "potful" is from the gregocentric system of units <FONTSIZE=2>[note: Content by Gregory Bennett]</FONT>, or GSU.One potful = 1 bag = 2 gadzillion = more than you can afford.</P><P>     Now, about that tempest in a teapot: actually, we're installinghardware designed in both systems into the International Space Station.Standard racks are measured in inches, but some of the fasteners aremetric.  For new hardware, computer-controlled milling machines don't givea flip, so we design it in the English system and label it in the metricsystem.  EVA bolts on the Japanese Experiment Module are metric-threadedbolts (because the Japanese government forces its industry to use metric)with 7/16-inch hex heads.  Custom- manufacturing all those bolts is pricey,but what the heck, the Japanese taxpayers won't know the difference.</P><P>     What we really need is for the General Conference on Weights andMeasures to give up their arrogant ways and just add all the units peopleuse to the International System of Units.</P><P>     All that said, I suspect that decades from now people will still stopoff for a pint at the Blue Earth Pub on their way home from a hard day'swork of putting up cubic whatevers of regolith; and they really won't worryabout whether it's an Imperial pint or a U. S. pint.</P><!-- Nav Bar --><hr size="5"><table align=center border=4 cellpadding = 3 cellspacing=2><tr><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/index.html">ArtemisProject</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/asi_index.html">ArtemisSociety</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/adb/index.html">ArtemisData Book</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="/adb/j/index.html">FAQ</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="/adb/04/index.html">Reference Mission</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.tlrc.com/catalog.html">Catalog</a></b></tr></table><hr size="5"><P><font size=-2>Copyright &#169; 1996 Artemis Society International.Updated Fri, Mar 8, 1996<br>Content by <a href="/bios/bennett.gregory.html">Gregory R. Bennett</a> <ahref="mailto:grb@asi.org">&lt;grb@asi.org&gt;</a>, maintained by <AHREF="MAILTO:simon@eagle.ca">&lt;simon@eagle.ca&gt;</A>.<br>"<a href="/Artemis.html">The Artemis Project</a>"is a trademark of <aHREF="http://www.tlrc.com/Lrc.html">The Lunar Resources Company</a>.</font></body></html>
