<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>M.3. Why the Moon Loses Gasses</TITLE></HEAD><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><!-- Artemis Data Book --><!-- ADB section M.3. The Lunar Environment --><!-- file: /adb/m/03/gas-retention.html --><!-- Keywords: luna moon lunar exploration space development artemisproject artemis data book --><!-- v 1.0 --><h2 align="center">Artemis Data Book</H2><h2 align="center">M.3. The Lunar Environment</H2><h2 align="center">Why the Moon Loses Gasses</H2><P ALIGN=CENTER><I>Gregory R. Bennett</I></P><P><HR><P><P>A gas is a collection of particles bouncing around.  The hotter the gasis, thefaster the particles move.  Also, the lighter the gas particles are, the fasterthey move at a given temperature.</P><P>On the earth, the gravity field is relatively high, and the range of surfacetemperatures isn't hot enough to cause the gas particles to reach escapevelocity.  So lightweight gasses stay in the atmosphere.</P><P>On the moon, surface temperatures reach 200 degrees, causing molecules of thelighter gasses (such as <a href="/adb/m/08/08/hydrogen.html">hydrogen</a>)to move faster to lunar escape velocity.  So theyescape into free space.</P><h3>Why this leads to water in special places on the lunar surface ...</h3><P>For lightweight substances to stick to the surface of the moon, they have tostay in a solid or liquid state.  In regions of extreme cold, these substancescan remain frozen in a solid state.  The only such region on the surface of themoon is in double-shadowed craters near the south pole.  (The antarctic regionof the moon starts at latitude 83 degrees South.)</P><P>Double-shadowed craters are craters whose rims are shadowed by other craters,100% of time.  This has allowed these surface regions to remain very, very coldfor a few billion years.  Anything that lands there, stays there,especially if it ends up covered with a layer of regolith for protectionagainst solar wind and cosmic ray sputtering, and the Moon's slight, butnot insignificant, inclination of 1 20'.</P><h3>What about beneath the surface ...</h3><P>A foot or two beneath the surface, the moon is a constant temperature, a fewdegrees below the freezing point of water.  Except for transient impacts, thesetemperature conditions have existed for 3 or 4 billion years.</P><P>We have no data about whether volatiles are trapped in the lunar refrigeratorthroughout the surface of the moon.  We probably won't know for sure until weget there and start digging.</P><!-- Nav Bar --><hr size="5"><table align=center border=4 cellpadding = 3 cellspacing=2><tr><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/index.html">ArtemisProject</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/asi_index.html">ArtemisSociety</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/adb/index.html">ArtemisData Book</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="/adb/j/index.html">FAQ</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="/adb/04/index.html">Reference Mission</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.tlrc.com/catalog.html">Catalog</a></b></tr></table><hr size="5"><font size=1>Copyright &#169; 1996 Artemis Society International.Updated Mon, Dec 9, 1996<br>Content by <a href="/bios/bennett.gregory.html">Gregory R. Bennett</a> <ahref="mailto:grb@asi.org">&lt;grb@asi.org&gt;</a>, maintained by <AHREF="MAILTO:simon@eagle.ca">&lt;simon@eagle.ca&gt;</A>.<br>"<a href="/Artemis.html">The Artemis Project</a>"is a trademark of <aHREF="http://www.tlrc.com/Lrc.html">The Lunar ResourcesCompany</a>.</font></body></html>
