<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>M.10.3.1. Lunar Gravity</TITLE></HEAD><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><!-- Artemis Data Book --><!-- ADB section M.10.3.1. Gravity --><!-- file: /adb/m/10/03/01/lunar-gravity.html --><!-- v 1.0 --><h2 align="center">Artemis Data Book</H2><h2 align="center">M.10.3.1. Gravity</H2><h2 align="center">Lunar Gravity</H2><P ALIGN=CENTER><I>Marvin Ostrega</I></P><P><HR><P><P>On the Moon, of course, gravity is comparatively weak. The Lunar Surfacegravity is 0.1622 m/s^2, compared to 9.8 m/s^2 of Earth. That is 16.5% ornearly exactly 1/6 Earth's gravity.</P><P>The comparative gravity is quite useful in field expeditions. Forexample, on Apollo 15, Scott and Irwin sampled a large boulder, the groundbeside it, and then were able to roll it over and sample the well-preservedmaterial underneath it in the low gravity.</P><P>The Lunar gravity field is uneven due to mascons (mass concentrations)near the surface. These are large, positive gravity analomalies which weredetected from doppler signals indicating <a href="/adb/m/02/06/">LunarOrbiter</a> satellite orbits were being disrupted. The largest gravityfield disturbences are in northern hemisphere at Mare Serenitatis and MareImbrium (mascons are usually associated with mare terrain). Mascons are yetto be satisfactorily explained.</P><P>Of course, low lunar gravity has many <ahref="/adb/04/03/05/">medical</a> and engineering implications discussed inother areas of the <a href="/adb/">Artemis Data Book</a>.</P><FONT SIZE=2><P>Reference:Chaikin, Andrew. A Man on the Moon. New York: Viking Penguin, 1994<BR>Heiken et al. Lunar Sourcebook: A User's Guide to the Moon. Cambridge:University of Cambridge Press, 1991</P></FONT><!-- Nav Bar --><hr size="5"><table align=center border=4 cellpadding = 3 cellspacing=2><tr><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/index.html">ArtemisProject</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/asi_index.html">ArtemisSociety</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.asi.org/adb/index.html">ArtemisData Book</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="/adb/j/index.html">FAQ</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="/adb/04/index.html">Reference Mission</a></b><td align=center> <b><a href="http://www.tlrc.com/catalog.html">Catalog</a></b></tr></table><hr size="5"><font size=1>Copyright &#169; 1996 Artemis Society International.Updated Sat, July 20, 1996<br>Content by Marvin Ostrega <ahref="mailto:ostrega@asi.org">&lt;ostrega@asi.org&gt;</a>, maintained by <AHREF="MAILTO:simon@eagle.ca">&lt;simon@eagle.ca&gt;</A>.<br>"<a href="/Artemis.html">The Artemis Project</a>"is a trademark of <aHREF="http://www.tlrc.com/Lrc.html">The Lunar ResourcesCompany</a>.</font></body></html>
